<SYNC Start=0><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=yellow>Dangerous Knowledge<br>
(2007.8.8 BBC Four)</font>
<SYNC Start=5000><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=5500><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=orange>딕테이션, 한/영 자막 제작<br>
DCinside 과학갤/다큐갤 '디핑'<br>
croydon.egloos.com</font>
<SYNC Start=10500><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=14287><P Class=KRCC>
자연을 지배하는 것은<br>
과학의 법칙입니다
<SYNC Start=18522><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=18799><P Class=KRCC>
그리고 그 아래에는 더욱<br>
심오한 규칙들이 숨어 있습니다
<SYNC Start=22820><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=22997><P Class=KRCC>
과학 법칙의 본질을 설명하며<br>
인간이 과학을 이해할 수 있게 돕는
<SYNC Start=29244><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=29342><P Class=KRCC>
수학 체계가 바로 그것입니다
<SYNC Start=33101><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=35970><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=lightgreen>한 알의 모래 속에서 세계를 보고<br>
한 송이 들꽃에서 천국을 보기 위해</font>
<SYNC Start=41832><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=41983><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=lightgreen>그대 손바닥 안에 무한을 붙들고<br>
순간 속에 영원을 담아라<br>
(from '순수의 전조' - 윌리엄 블레이크)</font>
<SYNC Start=48829><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=49131><P Class=KRCC>
신이 없다면, 이제<br>
어떤 사상에 의지해야 할까요?
<SYNC Start=55364><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=56333><P Class=KRCC>
특별히 주의를 기울이지 않으면<br>
언제든 나를 잡아먹어버릴..
<SYNC Start=61851><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=61897><P Class=KRCC>
멋져 보이지만<br>
매우 위험한 생각입니다
<SYNC Start=64665><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=67012><P Class=KRCC>
하지만 두려운 면도 있습니다.<br>
주저하며 뒤로 물러서게 되죠
<SYNC Start=72536><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=72806><P Class=KRCC>
그런데 이것은<br>
좋다 싫다의 문제가 아닙니다
<SYNC Start=76953><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=77133><P Class=KRCC>
증명이 되었고,<br>
받아들여야만 하는 것이죠
<SYNC Start=81560><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=81974><P Class=KRCC>
이것은 익숙하게 여겨왔던<br>
수학과 자연의 확실성을 와해시킨
<SYNC Start=86131><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=86247><P Class=KRCC>
소수의 뛰어난 학자들의<br>
업적에 대한 이야기입니다
<SYNC Start=91035><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=91331><P Class=KRCC>
또한, 이 문제에 사로잡혀<br>
정신이상이나 자살에 이를 지경까지
<SYNC Start=96463><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=96512><P Class=KRCC>
매달렸던 그들의 삶에 관한<br>
이야기이기도 합니다
<SYNC Start=103673><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=104084><P Class=KRCC>
비극적인 삶이었으나,<br>
그들이 밝혀낸것은 엄연한 진리입니다
<SYNC Start=108928><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=109231><P Class=KRCC>
그들의 업적은 당대에<br>
격렬한 반대에 부딪쳤으며
<SYNC Start=112544><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=112642><P Class=KRCC>
오늘날의 우리도<br>
완전히 계승하지 못했습니다
<SYNC Start=115384><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=115573><P Class=KRCC>
아직 그들이 조망한 새로운 세계의<br>
입구에 서 있을 뿐입니다
<SYNC Start=121738><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=123717><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=yellow>위험한 지식</font>
<SYNC Start=130902><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=148288><P Class=KRCC>
저는 데이빗 멀론입니다
<SYNC Start=150380><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=150588><P Class=KRCC>
잘 알려져 있지 않지만<br>
우리 시대에 커다란 영향을 끼친
<SYNC Start=156709><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=156804><P Class=KRCC>
4명의 위대한 지성,<br>
그리고 오늘날 시사하는 바가 큰
<SYNC Start=160833><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=160934><P Class=KRCC>
그들에 관한 이야기를<br>
들려드리고자 합니다
<SYNC Start=165844><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=172232><P Class=KRCC>
독일 동부의 작은 도시<br>
할레입니다
<SYNC Start=175816><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=175983><P Class=KRCC>
마틴 루터가 한때 여기서<br>
종교개혁을 설파하기도 했죠
<SYNC Start=179574><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=180547><P Class=KRCC>
이야기의 시작은<br>
이곳 대학의 수학 교수였던
<SYNC Start=184644><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=184663><P Class=KRCC>
게오르그 칸토어입니다.<br>
그는 비록 의도한건 아니지만
<SYNC Start=189489><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=189680><P Class=KRCC>
결국 수학과 과학의 토대를 뒤흔든<br>
대혁명의 시발점이 되었습니다
<SYNC Start=194996><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=195360><P Class=KRCC>
그것은 간단한 질문에서 시작되었죠
<SYNC Start=198558><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=198803><P Class=KRCC>
"도대체 무한은 얼마나 큰 것인가?"
<SYNC Start=201939><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=204249><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=yellow>- 신(神)의 전령 -</font>
<SYNC Start=210174><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=211928><P Class=KRCC>
칸토어는 정말 굉장하죠
<SYNC Start=214129><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=214366><P Class=KRCC>
제정신이 아닐만큼<br>
대단한 상상력의 소유자입니다
<SYNC Start=221055><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=221381><P Class=KRCC>
게오르그 칸토어는 세계 최고의<br>
수학자 중 한 명입니다
<SYNC Start=227008><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=232499><P Class=KRCC>
고대 그리스 이래 많은 수학자들이<br>
같은 의문을 품었습니다
<SYNC Start=237846><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=238182><P Class=KRCC>
누구도 감히 맞서지 못했던<br>
이 문제와 씨름하여
<SYNC Start=241682><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=241750><P Class=KRCC>
답을 찾은 것은 칸토어였습니다
<SYNC Start=244517><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=246072><P Class=KRCC>
그러나 그 대가를 치러야했죠
<SYNC Start=248650><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=251967><P Class=KRCC>
이것이 유일하게 남아있는<br>
칸토어의 흉상입니다
<SYNC Start=255068><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=255303><P Class=KRCC>
그가 세상을 뜨기<br>
1년 전에 만들어졌죠
<SYNC Start=258302><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=258655><P Class=KRCC>
그는 정신병원에서<br>
홀로 죽음을 맞았습니다
<SYNC Start=262412><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=263026><P Class=KRCC>
당대 최고 수학자의 정신을 병들게 한<br>
원인은 무엇이었을까요?
<SYNC Start=270092><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=279561><P Class=KRCC>
칸토어가 골몰한 주제는 단순히<br>
수학의 문제에 불과한 것이 아니었습니다
<SYNC Start=285362><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=285530><P Class=KRCC>
이것이 가지는 커다란 중요성을<br>
그도 처음부터 알고 있었습니다
<SYNC Start=291744><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=300365><P Class=KRCC>
그는 이를 통해 인간의 지성이<br>
진리와 확실성을 획득할거라 기대했지만
<SYNC Start=306743><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=306939><P Class=KRCC>
결국 자신의 연구가 그 확실성을<br>
더욱 더 멀어지게 만들고
<SYNC Start=313603><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=313743><P Class=KRCC>
결코 닿을수 없는 신기루로<br>
만들어버릴 것임은 알지 못했습니다
<SYNC Start=318636><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=326246><P Class=KRCC>
칸토어는 종교적인 사람이었습니다
<SYNC Start=329169><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=329271><P Class=KRCC>
그러나 일반적인 종교와는 달랐죠
<SYNC Start=332278><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=332447><P Class=KRCC>
그는 아마도<br>
이 교회에 온 적은 있지만
<SYNC Start=334998><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=335154><P Class=KRCC>
저기 보이는 신을 믿지는 않았습니다
<SYNC Start=337102><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=337264><P Class=KRCC>
그는 구원과 부활을 말하는<br>
신에는 관심이 없었습니다
<SYNC Start=342066><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=347718><P Class=KRCC>
그에게는 어릴적부터 들려오던<br>
목소리가 있었습니다
<SYNC Start=351001><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=351158><P Class=KRCC>
그의 표현을 빌면 '나를 수학으로<br>
인도하는 비밀의 목소리' 였죠
<SYNC Start=355464><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=355686><P Class=KRCC>
일평생 그를 따라다닌 목소리,<br>
이것이 칸토어의 신이었습니다
<SYNC Start=360736><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=361029><P Class=KRCC>
칸토어에겐 무한을 다루는<br>
그의 수학은 옳아야만 했습니다
<SYNC Start=365704><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=365848><P Class=KRCC>
진정 무한한 존재인<br>
신이 내려준 계시이기 때문이죠
<SYNC Start=370370><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=370583><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=lightgreen>지금은 알지 못하는 것들이<br>
모습을 드러낼 때가 오게 되리니..</font>
<SYNC Start=375490><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=376045><P Class=KRCC>
집합론에 관한 1895년 마지막 논문은<br>
세 줄의 경구로 시작합니다
<SYNC Start=382707><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=382848><P Class=KRCC>
그중 세번째는 성경의<br>
고린도전서에서 따온 것인데
<SYNC Start=386658><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=386996><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=cyan>조셉 도벤 - 과학사가, 뉴욕시립대학</font><br>
지금은 알지 못하는 것들이 결국<br>
모습을 드러낼 것이다.. 그런 내용이죠
<SYNC Start=392895><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=393079><P Class=KRCC>
칸토어는 정말로 자기가 신의 전령이며,<br>
미지의 대상이던 무한에 관한 이론을
<SYNC Start=398446><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=398568><P Class=KRCC>
이 세상으로 불러내는 사명을 띠고 있다고<br>
믿었던 것 같습니다
<SYNC Start=402994><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=403486><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=cyan>카린 리히터 - 수학자, 할레 대학</font><br>
칸토어의 종교적 입장과 수학은<br>
모순되는 것이 아닙니다
<SYNC Start=410390><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=411423><P Class=KRCC>
그는 자신의 수학적 영감을<br>
신이 주신 선물로 이해했습니다
<SYNC Start=418179><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=418570><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=cyan>그레고리 채이틴 - 수학자, IBM 연구소</font><br>
저는 칸토어가 신을 이해하려고<br>
노력한 것이라고 봅니다
<SYNC Start=421962><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=cyan>그레고리 채이틴 - 수학자, IBM 연구소</font><br>
'수학 신학'.. 쯤 될까요?<br>
그런 방향이었다고 생각합니다
<SYNC Start=426402><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=427050><P Class=KRCC>
칸토어가 믿은 신은 조물주 신이며,<br>
따라서 그의 진리는
<SYNC Start=432093><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=432434><P Class=KRCC>
만물의 운동을 지배하는<br>
영원하고 완벽한 운동 법칙입니다
<SYNC Start=436820><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=438844><P Class=KRCC>
이 운동 법칙을 이해함으로써 우리는
<SYNC Start=442247><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=442445><P Class=KRCC>
자연을 곡선, 운동 궤적, 힘 같은<br>
관점으로 바라보게 되었으며
<SYNC Start=447293><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=447410><P Class=KRCC>
현대에는 마침내<br>
달까지 여행할 수 있었습니다
<SYNC Start=451083><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=451848><P Class=KRCC>
신이 창조하고 뉴턴과 라이프니츠<font color=magenta>*</font>가 발견한<br>
영원불멸한 확실성의 세계입니다<br>
<font color=magenta>* 현대적인 미적분학의 창시자들</font>
<SYNC Start=457943><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=458246><P Class=KRCC>
그런데 그 핵심에는<br>
'무한'이라는 골칫거리가 있습니다
<SYNC Start=463968><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=465006><P Class=KRCC>
운동궤적의 매끈한 곡선은,<br>
사실 뜯어보면 매끈하지 않습니다
<SYNC Start=470489><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=470586><P Class=KRCC>
무한히 짧은 선분들이<br>
무한히 많이 모인 것입니다
<SYNC Start=474933><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=475159><P Class=KRCC>
각각의 선분은<br>
정지된 순간에 해당하죠
<SYNC Start=478154><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=478350><P Class=KRCC>
이것들을 영화 필름처럼 늘어놓으면<br>
원래의 운동 궤적이 얻어집니다
<SYNC Start=483642><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=483837><P Class=KRCC>
분명히 무한의 개념이 들어있지만,<br>
어쨌든 잘 들어맞습니다
<SYNC Start=486925><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=487113><P Class=KRCC>
그래서, 이해하기 힘든 무한이란 개념은<br>
다들 모른척 피했습니다
<SYNC Start=492083><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=492560><P Class=KRCC>
그러나 칸토어는 이 무한이라는<br>
핵심을 꼭 이해해야 한다고 생각했습니다
<SYNC Start=497616><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=497872><P Class=KRCC>
칸토어는 종교적인 인간이었죠
<SYNC Start=499966><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=500086><P Class=KRCC>
따라서 그에겐 저 수학 기호<font color=magenta>(∞ 무한대)</font>가<br>
종교적 진리이기도 한 것입니다
<SYNC Start=505455><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=505720><P Class=KRCC>
신은 수학을 이용하여<br>
만물의 운행을 관장합니다
<SYNC Start=509221><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=509462><P Class=KRCC>
바로 그 수학의 핵심에<br>
무한의 신비가 숨어있죠
<SYNC Start=513186><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=514218><P Class=KRCC>
그러나 무한의 신비를 터득하려는<br>
노력은 모두 실패하였습니다
<SYNC Start=519169><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=520233><P Class=KRCC>
근대에 최초로 도전장을<br>
던진 것은 갈릴레오였습니다
<SYNC Start=524597><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=524920><P Class=KRCC>
그의 접근법은 원을 이용한 것입니다
<SYNC Start=527563><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=527795><P Class=KRCC>
이런것입니다
<SYNC Start=528808><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=528979><P Class=KRCC>
여기 원을 그립니다
<SYNC Start=531621><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=532304><P Class=KRCC>
이 원에 내접하는 삼각형,<br>
또 사각형, 오각형,..을 그립니다
<SYNC Start=536531><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=536777><P Class=KRCC>
뭔가 보이시나요?
<SYNC Start=539163><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=539334><P Class=KRCC>
원은 바로 무한히 짧은 변들이<br>
무한히 많이 모인 다각형이로군요
<SYNC Start=543723><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=544062><P Class=KRCC>
신기하죠?<br>
단순한 원에도 무한이 들어있습니다
<SYNC Start=548697><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=549009><P Class=KRCC>
그런데 이 관찰은<br>
괴이한 모순을 낳습니다
<SYNC Start=553843><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=554511><P Class=KRCC>
바깥에 좀더 큰 원을 그려 볼까요
<SYNC Start=558344><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=558505><P Class=KRCC>
이제 지극히 날카로운 연필로,<br>
원의 중심으로부터..
<SYNC Start=562630><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=562669><P Class=KRCC>
안쪽 원을 이루는 (무한히 짧은) 선분들<br>
각각에 이르는 가느다란 직선들을 긋습니다
<SYNC Start=567812><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=567970><P Class=KRCC>
지금 그은 직선들은 무한히 많습니다.<br>
그럼 안쪽 원을 가득 채우겠죠?
<SYNC Start=570775><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=570854><P Class=KRCC>
이제 이 직선들을 바깥쪽 원까지 연장합니다.<br>
각각의 선들은 점점 벌어지죠?<br>
<SYNC Start=577262><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=577305><P Class=KRCC>
그럼 바깥쪽 원에 다다랐을 때는<br>
이 직선들 사이에 '틈'이 생기게 됩니다
<SYNC Start=581828><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=581843><P Class=KRCC>
바깥쪽 원을 채우기엔<br>
부족하다는 얘기죠!
<SYNC Start=584322><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=584537><P Class=KRCC>
갈릴레오 曰, "말도 안된다.<br>
무한히 많은 직선들로도 부족하다니?"
<SYNC Start=589912><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=590214><P Class=KRCC>
결국 그는, 신(神)이라면 몰라도..
<SYNC Start=592923><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=592959><P Class=KRCC>
유한한 존재인 인간은<br>
무한을 이해할수 없다고 결론내렸습니다
<SYNC Start=597562><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=597757><P Class=KRCC>
무한 개념이 꼭 필요하면 쓰되,<br>
그걸 이해하려고 들지는 말자는 거죠
<SYNC Start=603347><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=603566><P Class=KRCC>
바로 이러한 경향이<br>
칸토어 전까지 이어졌습니다
<SYNC Start=607520><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=611446><P Class=KRCC>
신(神)은 칸토어의 편에<br>
서 있는듯 했습니다
<SYNC Start=615983><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=616212><P Class=KRCC>
불과 몇년 동안, 그는<br>
결혼하고 가정을 꾸리고
<SYNC Start=619806><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=619993><P Class=KRCC>
무한에 관한 혁명적인<br>
첫번째 논문을 발표합니다
<SYNC Start=624675><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=625922><P Class=KRCC>
무한은 그저 끝없이 큰 수라고<br>
막연하게만 여겨 왔지만
<SYNC Start=629830><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=629861><P Class=KRCC>
칸토어는 전혀 새로운 경지를<br>
개척했습니다
<SYNC Start=633120><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=635264><P Class=KRCC>
칸토어의 참신한 발상은,<br>
"숫자 1에 1을 더할 수 있는데.."
<SYNC Start=641406><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=641781><P Class=KRCC>
".. 무한에 무한을 더하지 못할<br>
이유가 무엇인가? .."
<SYNC Start=648911><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=649390><P Class=KRCC>
"..그것도 가능할거야."<br>
이게 그 이론의 출발점이었습니다
<SYNC Start=654730><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=656401><P Class=KRCC>
그는 무한을 더하고 뺄 수<br>
있다는것 뿐만 아니라
<SYNC Start=660475><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=660548><P Class=KRCC>
무한을 대상으로 하는<br>
전혀 새로운 수학을 발견했습니다
<SYNC Start=665650><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=666371><P Class=KRCC>
'그래, 대충 이런게 무한이지'<br>
하고 넘어갔던 무한이란 것이
<SYNC Start=670501><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=670599><P Class=KRCC>
더이상 애매모호한 개념이 아님을<br>
처음으로 깨달았습니다
<SYNC Start=675100><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=675344><P Class=KRCC>
칸토어는 무한을 명확하고 엄밀한<br>
대상으로 다루는 방법을 알아냈습니다
<SYNC Start=680597><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=685952><P Class=KRCC>
1872년까지 칸토어는<br>
영감에 넘쳤습니다
<SYNC Start=689158><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=689552><P Class=KRCC>
그 누구도 알지 못했던<br>
무한의 실체도 이미 파악했죠
<SYNC Start=695338><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=695922><P Class=KRCC>
같은 해, 이곳 알프스에서
<SYNC Start=698501><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=698553><P Class=KRCC>
칸토어는 그의 이론을 이해하는<br>
유일한 사람을 만났습니다
<SYNC Start=701864><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=701998><P Class=KRCC>
수학자 리처드 데데킨트였죠
<SYNC Start=704081><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=704952><P Class=KRCC>
이때가 그의 삶에서 가장 행복하고<br>
지적으로 왕성하던 시절이었을겁니다
<SYNC Start=711493><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=712226><P Class=KRCC>
그 만남 후 1년만에<br>
그는 놀라운 발견을 해냅니다
<SYNC Start=716629><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=716926><P Class=KRCC>
무한보다 더 큰 무한이 있으며,
<SYNC Start=721781><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=721947><P Class=KRCC>
심지어 수많은 무한들의 세계에<br>
등급까지 있다는 사실입니다
<SYNC Start=726934><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=730644><P Class=KRCC>
직관적으로는 이상해 보이겠지만,
<SYNC Start=733154><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=733630><P Class=KRCC>
칸토어는 무한에도<br>
크고 작음이 있음을 간파했습니다
<SYNC Start=737980><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=738146><P Class=KRCC>
수직선(數直線) 위에는 무한히 많은<br>
정수와 유리수들이 놓여 있습니다
<SYNC Start=745625><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=745885><P Class=KRCC>
그런데 잘 살펴보면,<br>
이들의 개수는 무한히 많은데도
<SYNC Start=751237><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=751535><P Class=KRCC>
가까운 두 유리수 사이에도<br>
또다른 수들이 바글바글합니다
<SYNC Start=756841><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=756925><P Class=KRCC>
그것은 π 같은 무리수들로,
<SYNC Start=759125><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=759165><P Class=KRCC>
값을 표기하는데만도<br>
무한히 많은 자릿수가 필요합니다
<SYNC Start=763377><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=763710><P Class=KRCC>
놀랍게도 이 무리수들의 개수(무한)는<br>
유리수들의 개수(역시 무한)보다..
<SYNC Start=768267><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=768290><P Class=KRCC>
..비교도 안될만큼<br>
더 많다는 것이 밝혀졌습니다
<SYNC Start=771612><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=771928><P Class=KRCC>
'무한보다 더 큰 무한'의 존재를<br>
칸토어가 증명한 것입니다
<SYNC Start=778113><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=781704><P Class=KRCC>
칸토어의 천재성은 오늘날까지도<br>
수학자들을 고무시킵니다
<SYNC Start=787402><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=787747><P Class=KRCC>
그레고리 채이틴도<br>
그러한 석학 중 한명이죠
<SYNC Start=792003><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=792640><P Class=KRCC>
무한은 늘 존재했지만<br>
수학자들은 이것을 가둬놓았어요
<SYNC Start=799815><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=800098><P Class=KRCC>
'실제 무한'<font color=magenta>*</font>이니 '잠재 무한'<font color=magenta>*</font>이니<br>
하는 식으로 논하고 등등..<br>
<font color=magenta>* 실제로 무한한 값과, 유한한 값이지만<br>
한없이 커질 수 있는 값을 구분하던 용어</font>
<SYNC Start=804474><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=804610><P Class=KRCC>
반면에 칸토어는<br>
용감하게 나아갔습니다
<SYNC Start=808023><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=808263><P Class=KRCC>
그리하여 발견한 것이, 무한 위에<br>
그것보다 더 큰 무한, 더 큰 무한..
<SYNC Start=812208><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=812383><P Class=KRCC>
심지어 무한히 많은 무한들을 늘어놓아도<br>
이들 전부보다 더 큰 무한이 또 있고..
<SYNC Start=818749><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=818973><P Class=KRCC>
이렇게 큰 값들을 어떻게 이름 붙이고<br>
구분하겠나 싶죠?
<SYNC Start=823385><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=823414><P Class=KRCC>
이름을 다 붙일수도 없습니다
<SYNC Start=826421><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=826598><P Class=KRCC>
아무튼 환상적인 얘기죠
<SYNC Start=829745><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=829959><P Class=KRCC>
다시 말해 이런 것이었죠,<br>
"어떤 개념이든 가져오면 더 큰걸 만들어주마!"
<SYNC Start=834819><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=835130><P Class=KRCC>
궤변처럼 보일만도 합니다
<SYNC Start=837879><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=838391><P Class=KRCC>
그래서 애초부터 무한을 논하는것은<br>
대단히 어려운 문제입니다
<SYNC Start=844948><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=845248><P Class=KRCC>
칸토어가 엄청난 일을 한거죠
<SYNC Start=848021><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=848203><P Class=KRCC>
이것이 미분방정식, 건축, 항공공학<br>
같은것과 관계 없을지라도.. 뭐 어때요?
<SYNC Start=854514><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=855353><P Class=KRCC>
칸토어의 대담한 생각은 새로운 지평을 열고<br>
수학을 영원히 바꿔놓았습니다
<SYNC Start=862173><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=862362><P Class=KRCC>
그 자신도 그걸 알았죠
<SYNC Start=864246><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=864733><P Class=KRCC>
칸토어의 기분은 어땠을까요?
<SYNC Start=867003><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=867191><P Class=KRCC>
채이틴도 이런 심오한 발견의<br>
순간을 경험했습니다
<SYNC Start=872731><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=878581><P Class=KRCC>
울창한 숲 속을 걷습니다
<SYNC Start=881508><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=881759><P Class=KRCC>
사방이 나무로 빽빽해서<br>
길을 알아보기도 어렵죠
<SYNC Start=884627><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=884850><P Class=KRCC>
힘들고 지쳤지만 그래도<br>
열심히 걸어갑니다
<SYNC Start=889013><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=889163><P Class=KRCC>
겨우겨우 산을 오르며 둘러보면<br>
아름다운 경치가 드러납니다
<SYNC Start=895419><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=897353><P Class=KRCC>
운이 따르면<br>
산 정상에도 오를 수 있죠
<SYNC Start=902510><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=903693><P Class=KRCC>
이것은 어떤 초월적인 경험입니다
<SYNC Start=906854><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=907209><P Class=KRCC>
종교적인 사람이라면<br>
신에게 다가간 느낌이라고 할만한..
<SYNC Start=911156><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=914191><P Class=KRCC>
그럼 갑자기 모든 방향으로<br>
전망이 확 트이겠죠
<SYNC Start=918377><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=918460><P Class=KRCC>
모든것이 완전히 이해됩니다
<SYNC Start=921302><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=921796><P Class=KRCC>
이전에 알지 못하던 것을<br>
이해하는 것은 아름다운 일입니다
<SYNC Start=925628><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=925724><P Class=KRCC>
그런데 바로 그 순간,<br>
더 많은 새로운 문제들이 생겨납니다
<SYNC Start=930220><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=930341><P Class=KRCC>
이 산의 정상에 오르고 나면<br>
저 멀리 더 높은 산들이 보이는것이죠
<SYNC Start=936749><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=938197><P Class=KRCC>
칸토어의 이론은 비유하자면<br>
산 너머 더 높은 산들이 있고
<SYNC Start=941912><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=942292><P Class=KRCC>
아무리 많은 산을 올라도, 그 모두를<br>
능가하는 더 높은 산이 있다는 것입니다
<SYNC Start=948654><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=949164><P Class=KRCC>
이것은 어찌 보면 수학자들을<br>
자유롭게 놓아주는 발견일수 있습니다
<SYNC Start=952664><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=952888><P Class=KRCC>
하지만 두려운 면도 있습니다.<br>
주저하며 뒤로 물러서게 되죠
<SYNC Start=958291><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=960030><P Class=KRCC>
이 발견은 칸토어를 매혹시킨 반면,<br>
비판자들을 놀라게 했습니다
<SYNC Start=964053><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=964173><P Class=KRCC>
그들이 생각한 수학은<br>
명료함과 확실성을 추구하는 것입니다
<SYNC Start=967853><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=967989><P Class=KRCC>
무리수와 무한에 관한 칸토어의 생각은<br>
확실성을 훼손하는 것으로 보였으므로
<SYNC Start=975411><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=976080><P Class=KRCC>
그들은 칸토어를<br>
매우 적대시했습니다
<SYNC Start=979515><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=980882><P Class=KRCC>
칸토어가 평생을 보낸 대학의<br>
강의실입니다
<SYNC Start=985679><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=986059><P Class=KRCC>
제 생각에 칸토어는<br>
사면초가의 상태였을 것입니다
<SYNC Start=989847><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=990156><P Class=KRCC>
다른 수학자들은 칸토어가 논문을<br>
출판하지 못하게 막으려 했습니다
<SYNC Start=994483><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=994826><P Class=KRCC>
그는 늘 비엔나, 베를린 등의 명문대에서<br>
자신을 불러주기를 바랬지만
<SYNC Start=1000622><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1000736><P Class=KRCC>
결코 그런 일은 없었습니다
<SYNC Start=1002809><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1003157><P Class=KRCC>
게다가 인신공격까지 당했습니다
<SYNC Start=1005133><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1005245><P Class=KRCC>
위대한 수학자<br>
앙리 푸앙카레마저
<SYNC Start=1008320><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1008898><P Class=KRCC>
칸토어의 이론은<br>
수학이 잠깐 앓고 있는 질병일뿐이며
<SYNC Start=1011757><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1011829><P Class=KRCC>
곧 치료될 것이라고 했습니다
<SYNC Start=1013813><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1014022><P Class=KRCC>
심지어, 한때 친구이자<br>
스승이었던 크로네커는
<SYNC Start=1018412><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1018464><P Class=KRCC>
그를 '후학들을 망쳐놓는 존재'라며<br>
비난했습니다
<SYNC Start=1021523><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1021796><P Class=KRCC>
칸토어는 그의 이론과 함께<br>
이곳에 갇혀 있었던 셈입니다
<SYNC Start=1027518><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1027614><P Class=KRCC>
마치 병에 걸린 환자처럼요
<SYNC Start=1030254><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1030512><P Class=KRCC>
봉인을 풀고 보니까<br>
위험한 도깨비가 튀어나온겁니다
<SYNC Start=1034002><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1034073><P Class=KRCC>
왜냐면 이 개념은 본질적으로<br>
자기모순적인 측면이 있거든요
<SYNC Start=1040257><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1040720><P Class=KRCC>
사람들은 그 현실을 직시하기 싫어했고,<br>
대신 집합론을 축소시켜 버렸죠<br>
<font color=magenta>(칸토어가 현대적 집합론을 창조했고,<br>
무한집합에서 난점들이 발생했음)</font>
<SYNC Start=1045168><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1045395><P Class=KRCC>
'체르멜로-프랭켈 집합론'인데<br>
안전하지만 좀 김빠진 이론입니다
<SYNC Start=1051870><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1052090><P Class=KRCC>
그렇게 되니 재미있는 부분들도<br>
같이 날아가버렸습니다
<SYNC Start=1055613><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1055640><P Class=KRCC>
칸토어처럼 아슬아슬하게<br>
줄타기하는 편이 재밌는데 말이죠
<SYNC Start=1059196><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1059467><P Class=KRCC>
그러니까 어떤 것이냐면
<SYNC Start=1062178><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1062291><P Class=KRCC>
특별히 주의를 기울이지 않으면<br>
언제든 나를 잡아먹어버릴..
<SYNC Start=1065487><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1065570><P Class=KRCC>
멋져 보이지만 매우 위험한,<br>
자기모순에 가까운 논리들입니다
<SYNC Start=1070607><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1070800><P Class=KRCC>
예를 들어 '모든 것들의 집합'<br>
같은 개념은 자기모순을 낳습니다<br>
<font color=magenta>('러셀의 역설')</font>
<SYNC Start=1075103><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1076470><P Class=KRCC>
모두들 기겁했죠
<SYNC Start=1077894><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1079390><P Class=KRCC>
비판자들은, 칸토어가 수학의 생명인<br>
확실성과 명료함을 몰아내어
<SYNC Start=1085732><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1085875><P Class=KRCC>
그것을 영영 되찾지 못할까<br>
두려워했습니다
<SYNC Start=1088726><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1089081><P Class=KRCC>
그가 해결 불가능한 불확실성을<br>
수학으로 끌고온 것으로 보았기 때문이죠
<SYNC Start=1095636><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1096333><P Class=KRCC>
이론을 완결지어야 반대파를 설득할수<br>
있음을 칸토어도 알고 있었습니다
<SYNC Start=1101294><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1101635><P Class=KRCC>
무한에 대한 총체적인 논리 체계를<br>
세울 수 있을까요?
<SYNC Start=1107824><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1109271><P Class=KRCC>
그가 반드시 밝혀내야만 할 것은<br>
무한들 사이의 관계입니다
<SYNC Start=1114213><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1114486><P Class=KRCC>
성공한다면 완벽한 이론이 되지만
<SYNC Start=1117665><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1117927><P Class=KRCC>
그렇지 못하면<br>
불완전한 조각들에 불과합니다
<SYNC Start=1121016><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1121466><P Class=KRCC>
무한들 사이의 관계에 대한 문제,
<SYNC Start=1124706><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1124966><P Class=KRCC>
이것이 바로 '연속체 가설'입니다
<SYNC Start=1128299><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1129425><P Class=KRCC>
그는 고립된 속에서도<br>
반대를 무릅쓰고 더욱 노력했습니다
<SYNC Start=1135119><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1135444><P Class=KRCC>
여느 사람이라면 포기했겠지만<br>
그는 달랐습니다
<SYNC Start=1138986><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1143440><P Class=KRCC>
임상심리학자<br>
루이스 새스의 추측은
<SYNC Start=1146911><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1147031><P Class=KRCC>
고립되길 두려워하지 않는 태도가<br>
칸토어의 천재성을 발현시켰다는 것입니다
<SYNC Start=1152785><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1153634><P Class=KRCC>
당연하게 여기던 지식에<br>
안주하지 않고
<SYNC Start=1157684><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1157830><P Class=KRCC>
한발 더 나아가려는<br>
의지가 필수적입니다
<SYNC Start=1161636><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1161719><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=cyan>루이스 새스 - 임상심리학자, 럿거스 대학</font><br>
그런데 그러한 사람이라면<br>
결국 역외자 취급을 받기 십상입니다
<SYNC Start=1167615><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1168052><P Class=KRCC>
단순히 학문적인 이유에서만<br>
그런 것은 아닙니다
<SYNC Start=1173661><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1173859><P Class=KRCC>
개인적인 성격이나 성향도<br>
그 이유가 됩니다
<SYNC Start=1176662><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1176698><P Class=KRCC>
남들과 달리, 자연스럽지 않은 것을<br>
자연스럽게 받아들이는 사람이니까요
<SYNC Start=1181369><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1184191><P Class=KRCC>
칸토어는 덫에 빠졌지만
<SYNC Start=1185734><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1185909><P Class=KRCC>
그의 삶에 비추어 보면<br>
포기는 생각도 못할 일이었습니다
<SYNC Start=1191391><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1192315><P Class=KRCC>
그는 어릴 때 아버지로부터<br>
받은 편지를
<SYNC Start=1195811><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1195968><P Class=KRCC>
가장 소중한 물건으로 여겨<br>
평생 가지고 다녔습니다
<SYNC Start=1201343><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1203525><P Class=KRCC>
그의 성공을 바라는 온가족의 마음이<br>
편지에 담겨 있었습니다
<SYNC Start=1208927><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1209080><P Class=KRCC>
또한 용기를 가지고<br>
비판과 반대를 이겨낼 것과
<SYNC Start=1214652><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1214800><P Class=KRCC>
신을 믿고 따르며<br>
단념하지 말 것을 부탁했습니다
<SYNC Start=1219239><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1222257><P Class=KRCC>
그는 그렇게 했습니다
<SYNC Start=1224226><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1225284><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=cyan>조셉 도벤 - 과학사가, 뉴욕시립대학</font><br>
칸토어가 옳다고 확신했던<br>
그 자신의 이론이
<SYNC Start=1230764><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1230820><P Class=KRCC>
문제의 근원에<br>
자리하고 있습니다
<SYNC Start=1234076><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1234230><P Class=KRCC>
신의 계시이기에<br>
옳다고 믿었던 이론이죠
<SYNC Start=1238579><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1238715><P Class=KRCC>
그 자신이 최초로 제시한 문제들을<br>
풀지 못했던 어려움에 대처하고
<SYNC Start=1244647><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1244840><P Class=KRCC>
무한의 문제를 다루었던<br>
그의 투쟁에는
<SYNC Start=1248502><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1248558><P Class=KRCC>
중요한 종교적 측면이 있습니다
<SYNC Start=1251610><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1256799><P Class=KRCC>
1884년까지 칸토어는 2년 이상<br>
연속체 가설과 씨름했습니다
<SYNC Start=1262318><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1262780><P Class=KRCC>
그에 대한 인격적, 학문적인 공격은<br>
날로 심해지고 있었죠
<SYNC Start=1268487><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1268755><P Class=KRCC>
버틸수 있을지 자신이 없다고<br>
친구에게 털어놓기도 했습니다
<SYNC Start=1272076><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1272183><P Class=KRCC>
결국, 버티지 못했습니다
<SYNC Start=1273755><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1273899><P Class=KRCC>
그해 5월경 그는 심각한<br>
신경쇠약에 걸렸습니다
<SYNC Start=1277086><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1277305><P Class=KRCC>
성격이 뒤바뀔 정도로 심했는데,<br>
그의 딸이 말하길
<SYNC Start=1280938><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1281200><P Class=KRCC>
사납게 고함을 치다가도 갑자기<br>
극단적으로 조용해지곤 했답니다
<SYNC Start=1286700><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1286984><P Class=KRCC>
결국 이곳 할레의 정신병원<br>
네르펜클리닉에 입원했습니다
<SYNC Start=1292717><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1294229><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=cyan>프랭크 필먼 - 정신과 의사, 할레 대학병원</font><br>
요즘 말로 하면<br>
그는 조울증이었습니다
<SYNC Start=1299154><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1299350><P Class=KRCC>
칸토어를 맡았던 의사들 대부분의<br>
진료 기록이 남아 있는데
<SYNC Start=1309730><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1309901><P Class=KRCC>
정신이 나가서<br>
소리를 지르기도 했고
<SYNC Start=1316029><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1316379><P Class=KRCC>
심각한 조증 발작으로<br>
매우 힘들어 했습니다
<SYNC Start=1322403><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1322587><P Class=KRCC>
때로는 화를 내기도 하고
<SYNC Start=1325467><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1326881><P Class=KRCC>
과대 망상이나 피해 망상에<br>
빠지기도 했습니다
<SYNC Start=1332617><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1359286><P Class=KRCC>
신경쇠약에 걸린 후로<br>
모든 것이 달라졌습니다
<SYNC Start=1362789><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1363858><P Class=KRCC>
친구에게 자신이 수학을 다시<br>
할수있을지 잘 모르겠다고도 했고
<SYNC Start=1367128><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1367328><P Class=KRCC>
수학 강의를 그만두고 철학을 강의하면<br>
안될지 대학에 문의하기도 했습니다
<SYNC Start=1371648><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1371969><P Class=KRCC>
그러나, 수학을 포기해야 할지<br>
회의하던 이 와중에도
<SYNC Start=1377086><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1378203><P Class=KRCC>
연속체 가설에 대한 연구는<br>
그만둔 적이 없었습니다
<SYNC Start=1381466><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1381526><P Class=KRCC>
도저히 이 문제를<br>
내려놓을수 없었나 봅니다
<SYNC Start=1385600><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1387287><P Class=KRCC>
증명을 찾아내야겠다,<br>
이런 생각밖에 안 듭니다
<SYNC Start=1390907><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1391638><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=cyan>카린 리히터 - 수학자, 할레 대학</font><br>
저도 이해가 가는데..<br>
수학자는 24시간 내내 수학자니까요
<SYNC Start=1397900><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1398183><P Class=KRCC>
수학은 삶의 일부입니다
<SYNC Start=1401977><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1402323><P Class=KRCC>
종일 수학에 대해 생각하게 되고,<br>
이 생각에서 떠나기는 어렵습니다
<SYNC Start=1409981><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1410182><P Class=KRCC>
계속 생각에 생각을 거듭하며
<SYNC Start=1412595><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1412806><P Class=KRCC>
'답을 찾아야 돼..'
<SYNC Start=1416054><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1416496><P Class=KRCC>
'답을 찾아야 돼..'<br>
계속 거기에 몰두하게 되죠
<SYNC Start=1420854><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1421480><P Class=KRCC>
1884년 8월,<br>
그의 연구를 누구보다 지지했던
<SYNC Start=1426607><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1426701><P Class=KRCC>
친구이자 동료인 미타그-레플러에게<br>
보낸 편지는 흥분에 차 있습니다
<SYNC Start=1432860><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1433057><P Class=KRCC>
여기서 그는 "마침내 해냈습니다.<br>
연속체 가설이 참임을 증명했습니다."
<SYNC Start=1437909><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1438243><P Class=KRCC>
그러면서 조만간<br>
증명을 보내겠다고 적었습니다
<SYNC Start=1441544><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1442228><P Class=KRCC>
그러나 감감무소식이었죠
<SYNC Start=1443884><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1444170><P Class=KRCC>
그리고 3개월 후<br>
두번째 편지에는
<SYNC Start=1447800><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1447907><P Class=KRCC>
칸토어의 당혹감이<br>
여실히 드러납니다
<SYNC Start=1451727><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1451824><P Class=KRCC>
"미안합니다, 증명했다는<br>
주장을 하지 말았어야 하는데.."
<SYNC Start=1455518><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1456092><P Class=KRCC>
"나의 아름다운 증명은<br>
모두 무너졌습니다."
<SYNC Start=1460392><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1461326><P Class=KRCC>
그 무너진 잔해를<br>
편지에서 볼 수 있습니다
<SYNC Start=1466163><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1468505><P Class=KRCC>
그런데 그로부터 3주 뒤
<SYNC Start=1470517><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1471364><P Class=KRCC>
이 편지에서는<br>
다른 주장을 합니다
<SYNC Start=1474632><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1475030><P Class=KRCC>
"연속체 가설이 거짓임을<br>
증명했습니다."
<SYNC Start=1479139><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1480404><P Class=KRCC>
이 패턴이 계속됩니다
<SYNC Start=1482216><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1482592><P Class=KRCC>
참이라고 증명했다가..
<SYNC Start=1485182><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1485394><P Class=KRCC>
또 거짓이라고 확신했다가..<br>
오락가락합니다
<SYNC Start=1488555><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1489086><P Class=KRCC>
그러면서 칸토어는<br>
서서히 미쳐 갔습니다
<SYNC Start=1494348><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1494782><P Class=KRCC>
초기 단계 증상 중의 하나는..
<SYNC Start=1497666><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1497694><P Class=KRCC>
또는 정신 분열 휴지기<br>
이전 단계의 증상은..
<SYNC Start=1501913><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1502021><P Class=KRCC>
환자가 주변 사물에<br>
지나치게 집중하는 것입니다
<SYNC Start=1508093><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1508210><P Class=KRCC>
말하자면 경직된 자세로<br>
인식하는 것입니다
<SYNC Start=1512267><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1516372><P Class=KRCC>
연속체 가설 앞에 좌절하면서,<br>
그는 무한을 협곡에 비유했습니다
<SYNC Start=1522986><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1523384><P Class=KRCC>
그가 본 것과 그가 아는 것<br>
사이에 있으나, 결코 닿을 수 없는..
<SYNC Start=1530554><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1533997><P Class=KRCC>
보통사람 같으면 별 의미가 없다고<br>
흘려 버릴 사물에 대해서도
<SYNC Start=1539911><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1540021><P Class=KRCC>
거기에 뭔가 상징이 숨어 있다고<br>
착각하는 것입니다
<SYNC Start=1545210><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1545554><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=lightgreen>찾아야 돼, 찾아야 돼..</font>
<SYNC Start=1549543><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1558233><P Class=KRCC>
뭔가를 이해하려면 그것을<br>
자세히 들여다봐야 하죠
<SYNC Start=1561856><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1561969><P Class=KRCC>
하지만, 한발 물러나 전체적인<br>
맥락을 보는 능력 또한 필요합니다
<SYNC Start=1566740><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1567005><P Class=KRCC>
대상에만 지나치게 집중하는 사람은<br>
이런 맥락을 놓치게 됩니다
<SYNC Start=1571213><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1577709><P Class=KRCC>
칸토어는 완전히 회복되지 못했습니다
<SYNC Start=1579670><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1579794><P Class=KRCC>
그는 풀지 못할 문제와 싸우며<br>
여생을 보냈고
<SYNC Start=1584842><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1585195><P Class=KRCC>
좌절할 때마다<br>
깊은 상처를 입었습니다
<SYNC Start=1589084><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1609761><P Class=KRCC>
1899년, 그는 다시 한번<br>
연속체 가설을 붙들었고
<SYNC Start=1614626><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1614908><P Class=KRCC>
또다시 상태가 나빠져<br>
정신병원으로 되돌아왔습니다
<SYNC Start=1618664><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1619306><P Class=KRCC>
그리고 다시 회복될 무렵
<SYNC Start=1622370><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1622998><P Class=KRCC>
아들 루돌프가 열세살 생일을<br>
나흘 앞두고 갑자기 죽었습니다
<SYNC Start=1629194><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1639471><P Class=KRCC>
그는 친구에게 쓴 편지에서
<SYNC Start=1641401><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1641450><P Class=KRCC>
아들이 자신으로부터 물려받은<br>
음악적 재능을 언급했습니다
<SYNC Start=1645957><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1646362><P Class=KRCC>
칸토어는 수학을 하기 위해<br>
음악을 포기했죠
<SYNC Start=1650709><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1651297><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=lime>루돌프 칸토어 1886-1899</font><br>
아들이 죽자, 그는 이제
<SYNC Start=1653465><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1653539><P Class=KRCC>
음악에 대한 자신의 꿈도<br>
함께 죽었다고 느꼈습니다
<SYNC Start=1658211><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1679787><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=lightgreen>아빠!</font>
<SYNC Start=1681071><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1688041><P Class=KRCC>
칸토어는 자신이 왜 음악 대신<br>
수학을 택했었는지조차
<SYNC Start=1693622><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1693690><P Class=KRCC>
기억이 나지 않는다고<br>
말하기도 했습니다
<SYNC Start=1696685><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1696854><P Class=KRCC>
그를 수학으로 불러들이고<br>
삶과 연구에 의미를 부여했던..
<SYNC Start=1704350><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1704727><P Class=KRCC>
신이라고 믿었던 비밀의 목소리..
<SYNC Start=1707121><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1707476><P Class=KRCC>
그 목소리마저 그를 버렸습니다
<SYNC Start=1710646><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1713477><P Class=KRCC>
칸토어의 이야기는<br>
일단 여기까지입니다
<SYNC Start=1715872><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1716060><P Class=KRCC>
시대적인 맥락을 무시하고<br>
칸토어의 삶만 보면
<SYNC Start=1719128><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1719162><P Class=KRCC>
단지 불운한 개인의 삶으로<br>
생각될 수도 있습니다
<SYNC Start=1724356><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1724693><P Class=KRCC>
그러나, 칸토어가 판도라의 상자를<br>
연 것이 아닐까 하는 불길함은
<SYNC Start=1728998><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1729064><P Class=KRCC>
돌처럼 단단해 보이던 것이<br>
모래처럼 손에서 빠져나가는 듯한
<SYNC Start=1732477><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1732503><P Class=KRCC>
한층 더 넓은 범위의<br>
불안감으로 이어집니다
<SYNC Start=1735415><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1735604><P Class=KRCC>
같은 시기 루트비히 볼츠만의 이야기는<br>
이 불안감을 더 잘 드러냅니다
<SYNC Start=1741559><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1743197><P Class=KRCC>
칸토어가 수학에서 혁명적인<br>
아이디어를 냈다가 배척당한 것처럼
<SYNC Start=1746861><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1747046><P Class=KRCC>
동시대의 볼츠만도 물리학에서<br>
비슷한 일을 겪었습니다
<SYNC Start=1752871><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1753846><P Class=KRCC>
루트비히 볼츠만의 묘입니다
<SYNC Start=1755902><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1756390><P Class=KRCC>
저것이 그를 죽인 방정식입니다
<SYNC Start=1760284><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1760456><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=magenta>(볼츠만 방정식)</font>
<SYNC Start=1763475><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1769303><P Class=KRCC>
칸토어처럼 볼츠만의 아이디어도<br>
시기를 잘못 만난 탓이었습니다
<SYNC Start=1775369><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1779357><P Class=KRCC>
칸토어가 영원하고 완벽한 논리라는<br>
수학의 이상에 흠집을 냈다면
<SYNC Start=1783708><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1784306><P Class=KRCC>
볼츠만의 공식은 영원한 질서라는<br>
물리학의 이상에 도전한 것입니다
<SYNC Start=1790655><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1791076><P Class=KRCC>
이들은 수학, 물리를 넘어 확실성이라는<br>
일반적인 개념을 허물었습니다
<SYNC Start=1798950><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1799362><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=yellow>- 무질서의 천재 -</font>
<SYNC Start=1805730><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1808130><P Class=KRCC>
볼츠만과 칸토어의 시대는<br>
과학, 철학 뿐만 아니라
<SYNC Start=1811239><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1811481><P Class=KRCC>
정치, 예술 등에서도<br>
확실성을 열망하던 때였습니다
<SYNC Start=1815351><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1819262><P Class=KRCC>
겉보기에는 단단해 보이지만<br>
알맹이는 흔들거리는 시대였습니다
<SYNC Start=1826098><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1826691><P Class=KRCC>
구식 질서는 점점 쇠퇴하고<br>
곧 불행이 다가올 조짐이 보였습니다
<SYNC Start=1834097><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1834865><P Class=KRCC>
카를 크라우스가 '종말의 실험실'<font color=magenta>*</font>이라<br>
불렀던 비엔나에서는<br>
<font color=magenta>* 구시대와 현대가 교차하는 1900년 무렵<br>
비엔나의 세기말적 분위기를 비유한 표현</font>
<SYNC Start=1841144><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1841318><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=cyan>카를 지그문트 - 수학자, 비엔나 대학</font><br>
합스부르크 제국의 몰락이<br>
멀지 않았다는 관측이 있었습니다
<SYNC Start=1850158><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1853283><P Class=KRCC>
아주 기묘한 시대였습니다
<SYNC Start=1855860><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1856183><P Class=KRCC>
한편에서는 권력층이 20년씩이나 걸려<br>
오스트리아 제국의 기념 건물을 만들어
<SYNC Start=1862537><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1862553><P Class=KRCC>
현재의 질서가 영원하리라고<br>
선언했습니다
<SYNC Start=1868140><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1870710><P Class=KRCC>
부자는 언제나 성 안에..
<SYNC Start=1873739><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1873944><P Class=KRCC>
빈자는 언제나 성 밖에..
<SYNC Start=1876886><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1877804><P Class=KRCC>
그러나 사실 한편으로는<br>
제국은 거의 망하기 직전이었습니다
<SYNC Start=1882538><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1882820><P Class=KRCC>
당대 지식인층의 경향을<br>
시인 호프만슈탈은 이렇게 요약했습니다
<SYNC Start=1887822><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1887959><P Class=KRCC>
구세대에서는 단단한 것으로<br>
믿어왔던 것들이 사실은..
<SYNC Start=1894934><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1895061><P Class=KRCC>
그의 표현을 빌면 'das Gleitende'
<SYNC Start=1897678><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1898118><P Class=KRCC>
즉 '미끄러져 빠져나간다'는 것입니다
<SYNC Start=1901440><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1903741><P Class=KRCC>
그 표현이 비엔나.. 그리고 다른 곳들의<br>
시대적 분위기를 말해준다고 생각합니다
<SYNC Start=1909868><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1909936><P Class=KRCC>
아직 무너지진 않았지만<br>
곧 그렇게 될 것처럼 보이는
<SYNC Start=1914838><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1914951><P Class=KRCC>
제국의 수도인 비엔나 분위기를<br>
특히 잘 묘사한 문구 같습니다
<SYNC Start=1921504><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1925145><P Class=KRCC>
볼츠만 시대의 과학적 의문들은<br>
이러한 배경에 반하는 것이었습니다
<SYNC Start=1931363><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1934701><P Class=KRCC>
비엔나 대학의 안마당입니다
<SYNC Start=1937329><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1937619><P Class=KRCC>
이곳을 거친 유명한 학자들의 흉상들<br>
사이에 볼츠만의 것도 있습니다
<SYNC Start=1942679><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1943050><P Class=KRCC>
그러나 이 많은 사람들 중<br>
동시대인 상당수가
<SYNC Start=1947368><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1947538><P Class=KRCC>
입을 모아 볼츠만의 이론에<br>
반대했습니다
<SYNC Start=1950209><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1951312><P Class=KRCC>
그것은 과학적인 측면만큼이나<br>
이념적인 반대였습니다
<SYNC Start=1955888><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1957188><P Class=KRCC>
그때까지의 물리학은 확실성과<br>
질서가 뚜렷한 세계관이었습니다
<SYNC Start=1962814><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1963016><P Class=KRCC>
신이 내린 영구적이며 예측 가능한<br>
법칙에 의해 결정되는 질서이죠
<SYNC Start=1968088><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1969184><P Class=KRCC>
볼츠만은, 질서는<br>
신이 부여한 것이 아니라
<SYNC Start=1974891><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1974956><P Class=KRCC>
원자들의 무작위적인 충돌로부터<br>
비롯되는 것이라고 제안했습니다
<SYNC Start=1979501><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1979628><P Class=KRCC>
당시에는 급진적인 생각이었지만<br>
지금은 우리의 세계관의 기초이죠
<SYNC Start=1985337><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1988363><P Class=KRCC>
볼츠만이 삶을 마감한 곳에서 멀지 않은<br>
아드리아 해안의 트리에스테에서
<SYNC Start=1992778><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1992877><P Class=KRCC>
거주하며 일하고 있는<br>
무사르도 교수를 만났습니다
<SYNC Start=1995834><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1995943><P Class=KRCC>
볼츠만에 관한 전문가이며,<br>
같은 분야를 연구하고 있습니다
<SYNC Start=2000301><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2000945><P Class=KRCC>
그가 독일 물리학자들에게<br>
충분히 인정받지 못한
<SYNC Start=2006848><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2006896><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=cyan>쥬세페 무사르도 - 물리학자, 트리에스테 국제고등과학원</font><br>
두가지 이유가<br>
있었다고 생각합니다
<SYNC Start=2012589><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2012901><P Class=KRCC>
우선, 그의 이론은 눈에 보이지 않는<br>
원자에 기반한 것입니다
<SYNC Start=2021239><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2022560><P Class=KRCC>
당대 가장 영향력 있는<br>
과학철학자였던 에른스트 마흐가
<SYNC Start=2027338><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2027565><P Class=KRCC>
극렬히 비판했던 것도<br>
이 점이었습니다
<SYNC Start=2033602><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2033983><P Class=KRCC>
마흐의 비판은 이겁니다:
<SYNC Start=2036758><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2036880><P Class=KRCC>
"볼 수도 없고 필요도 없는 원자를 왜<br>
가정하고, 논의에 포함시켜야 하는가?"
<SYNC Start=2044047><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2045421><P Class=KRCC>
보이지 않는 원자의 존재를<br>
주장하는 것도 모자라서
<SYNC Start=2049273><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2049471><P Class=KRCC>
행동을 예측하기 어려운 원자를<br>
물리학의 근본으로 삼는다는 것은
<SYNC Start=2055573><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2055793><P Class=KRCC>
확실성보다는 확률에 기반한<br>
전혀 새로운 종류의 물리학을 뜻합니다
<SYNC Start=2062197><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2064202><P Class=KRCC>
두번째 이유는..<br>
이것도 혁명적인 생각인데
<SYNC Start=2068284><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2068808><P Class=KRCC>
물리학에 확률을 도입하고, 나아가<br>
확률의 역할을 강조했다는 것입니다
<SYNC Start=2077059><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2078726><P Class=KRCC>
사람들은 딱 부러지는<br>
물리 법칙에 익숙해져 있었죠
<SYNC Start=2086206><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2087791><P Class=KRCC>
영구 불변이며 불확실함 따위는<br>
허용하지 않는 법칙 말입니다
<SYNC Start=2093773><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2094175><P Class=KRCC>
그가 무대에 올려놓은 두가지,<br>
즉 눈에 보이지 않는 '원자'..
<SYNC Start=2100218><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2100302><P Class=KRCC>
그리고 '확률', 즉 확실성 대신<br>
가능성의 예측만 허용한다는 관점..
<SYNC Start=2109128><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2109331><P Class=KRCC>
이것들은 당시 과학적 세계관과<br>
크게 상반되는 것이었습니다
<SYNC Start=2115963><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2116280><P Class=KRCC>
그래서 문제가 생겼죠
<SYNC Start=2120505><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2122201><P Class=KRCC>
볼츠만의 천재성은<br>
확률을 기꺼이 수용했다는 것입니다
<SYNC Start=2126385><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2126671><P Class=KRCC>
기존의 기계론적인 물리학으로는<br>
결코 이해할 수 없었던
<SYNC Start=2132672><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2132804><P Class=KRCC>
불, 물, 생명 같은 복잡한 현상들을<br>
이해하는 단초를 얻은 것입니다
<SYNC Start=2137768><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2138289><P Class=KRCC>
그러나 그 이론은 확률에 의존하므로<br>
확실성을 훼손하는 것으로 여겨져
<SYNC Start=2144348><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2144408><P Class=KRCC>
아무도 귀기울이지 않았습니다
<SYNC Start=2146802><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2151002><P Class=KRCC>
그 또한 칸토어와 마찬가지로<br>
무자비한 반대에 부딪쳤고
<SYNC Start=2154936><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2154970><P Class=KRCC>
무척 힘들어 했습니다
<SYNC Start=2158807><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2159710><P Class=KRCC>
볼츠만은 때와 장소를<br>
잘못 만난 것 같군요
<SYNC Start=2162602><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2162752><P Class=KRCC>
물론, 물론입니다, 맞아요..
<SYNC Start=2167132><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2170203><P Class=KRCC>
20년만 뒤에 들고 나왔더라도..
<SYNC Start=2172782><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2172881><P Class=KRCC>
더 늦게, 그리고 잉글랜드였다면<br>
당대 최고 물리학자 대접을 받았을걸요
<SYNC Start=2180008><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2180220><P Class=KRCC>
만나는 이들마다 적이었다고나 할까요,<br>
에른스트 마흐와도 무척 자주 마주쳤는데..
<SYNC Start=2191621><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2191802><P Class=KRCC>
- 사방이 적이고, 아군은 없고..<br>
- 아군은 없고, 맞아요
<SYNC Start=2194585><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2198304><P Class=KRCC>
볼츠만의 생각이 당시의 관념에 비추어<br>
급진적이었다는 것은 쉽게 알 수 있습니다
<SYNC Start=2203608><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2203907><P Class=KRCC>
과학이 아닌 사회적 관점에서<br>
특히 그렇죠
<SYNC Start=2208547><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2209835><P Class=KRCC>
전통적인 과학에는 신이 창조한 세계라는<br>
관점이 깃들어 있습니다
<SYNC Start=2215436><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2215541><P Class=KRCC>
완벽하고 영원한 법칙들에 의해<br>
반석 위에 놓여진 삼라만상의 세계..
<SYNC Start=2220114><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2220366><P Class=KRCC>
만물은 저마다 정해진 제자리가 있고<br>
예측 가능하게 움직인다는 시각입니다
<SYNC Start=2225833><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2227063><P Class=KRCC>
이곳 비엔나 중앙 묘지야말로<br>
어찌보면 그 이상적인 표본입니다
<SYNC Start=2233583><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2233714><P Class=KRCC>
모든 것이 예측 가능하고,<br>
모든 이가 정해진 자리를 차지하고 있죠
<SYNC Start=2239614><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2240076><P Class=KRCC>
그러나 이런 확실성이<br>
정치적으로는 바람직할지라도
<SYNC Start=2245671><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2245714><P Class=KRCC>
생명이 살아숨쉬는, 열역학이 지배하는,<br>
진짜 세상은 이런 모습이 아닙니다
<SYNC Start=2252219><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2254879><P Class=KRCC>
완벽하고 영원한 세상은<br>
변화가 없는 죽은 세상입니다
<SYNC Start=2259522><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2259619><P Class=KRCC>
열역학의 세상, 진짜 세상은<br>
끊임없는 변화에 의해 유지됩니다
<SYNC Start=2265934><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2268005><P Class=KRCC>
물론, 변화는 생명을 부여하지만<br>
무질서와 쇠퇴도 함께 가져다줍니다
<SYNC Start=2274676><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2275342><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=cyan>로저 펜로즈 - 수학자, 옥스포드 대학</font><br>
그런데 문제가 생깁니다. 뉴턴 역학은<br>
시간에 대해 대칭적, 가역적이죠
<SYNC Start=2282187><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2282249><P Class=KRCC>
그렇다면, 시간에 대해<br>
대칭적인 기본 원리들로부터
<SYNC Start=2285938><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2286154><P Class=KRCC>
시간에 대해 비대칭적인 법칙이<br>
어떻게 생겨날 수 있을까요?
<SYNC Start=2289367><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2290096><P Class=KRCC>
시간의 방향을 거꾸로 돌려도<br>
뉴턴 물리학은 아무 문제가 없습니다
<SYNC Start=2293842><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2294124><P Class=KRCC>
그런데도 엔트로피는<br>
'미래'로 갈수록 증가한단 말이죠
<SYNC Start=2296894><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2300644><P Class=KRCC>
무질서와 쇠퇴가<br>
얼마나 축적되었는가,
<SYNC Start=2304783><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2304869><P Class=KRCC>
이것이 바로 볼츠만이 엔트로피를<br>
이해한 방식입니다
<SYNC Start=2309339><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2314086><P Class=KRCC>
그 자체가 시간의 화살입니다
<SYNC Start=2316666><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2316807><P Class=KRCC>
사물이 점점 무질서해지는 방향이<br>
시간의 화살의 방향이죠
<SYNC Start=2323410><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2323747><P Class=KRCC>
자연의 근본적인 경향성이며, 볼츠만은<br>
이것을 정확하게 정량화했습니다<br>
<font color=magenta>(묘비에 적혀 있던 볼츠만 방정식)</font>
<SYNC Start=2329784><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2331104><P Class=KRCC>
저는 그를 '무질서의 천재'라고 부릅니다
<SYNC Start=2334686><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2338227><P Class=KRCC>
엔트로피에 관한 볼츠만의 연구는
<SYNC Start=2340944><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2340956><P Class=KRCC>
모든 계가 완벽함을 잃고<br>
무질서해지는 이유를 설명합니다
<SYNC Start=2345933><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2346059><P Class=KRCC>
물리학에서 말하는 시간 개념도<br>
새로이 정립했습니다
<SYNC Start=2349737><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2355521><P Class=KRCC>
고전 물리학에서는 시간과 모든것이<br>
앞으로든 뒤로든 흐를 수 있습니다
<SYNC Start=2362328><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2362886><P Class=KRCC>
그러나 열역학에서는, 적어도 시간만큼은<br>
앞으로만 흐를 수 있습니다
<SYNC Start=2371172><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2374494><P Class=KRCC>
엔트로피 개념은 철학적, 정치적으로도<br>
중요한 영향을 끼쳤습니다
<SYNC Start=2379848><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2380325><P Class=KRCC>
엔트로피는 결국 시간의 흐름은<br>
만물의 쇠퇴로 이어짐을 의미합니다
<SYNC Start=2385871><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2386130><P Class=KRCC>
젊음에서 노년으로 변해가는<br>
거역할 수 없는 흐름의 원리입니다
<SYNC Start=2391178><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2393595><P Class=KRCC>
쇠퇴를 의미하는 엔트로피 앞에서는<br>
그 무엇도 영원할 수 없습니다
<SYNC Start=2398519><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2405452><P Class=KRCC>
볼츠만의 방정식은<br>
숙명적인 유한함을 의미합니다
<SYNC Start=2410875><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2415268><P Class=KRCC>
물리학은 이제 신이 부여한 질서조차<br>
영원할 수 없음을 선언했습니다
<SYNC Start=2422401><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2426658><P Class=KRCC>
신이 못박아 놓은 자연의 질서란<br>
존재하지 않는다는 통찰은
<SYNC Start=2430780><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2430786><P Class=KRCC>
볼츠만이 가장 존경했던 한 과학자가<br>
이미 지적한 바 있습니다
<SYNC Start=2435080><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2435749><P Class=KRCC>
찰스 다윈입니다
<SYNC Start=2437565><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2441942><P Class=KRCC>
영원한 완전무결함이 사라진 자리는<br>
진화와 멸종의 파도가 대신합니다
<SYNC Start=2447199><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2447926><P Class=KRCC>
이러한 끊임없는 변화라는 개념을
<SYNC Start=2450322><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2450386><P Class=KRCC>
볼츠만은 엔트로피 방정식을 통해<br>
물리학의 핵심 원리로 도입한 것입니다
<SYNC Start=2456444><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2462137><P Class=KRCC>
볼츠만도 이러한 유사성을<br>
거의 확실히 인지하고 있었습니다
<SYNC Start=2466262><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2466912><P Class=KRCC>
자신의 세대가 어떻게 기억될것으로<br>
생각하냐는 질문에 그는,
<SYNC Start=2470472><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2470692><P Class=KRCC>
물리학의 세기가 아닌<br>
다윈의 세기로 기억될거라고 했습니다
<SYNC Start=2476147><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2477764><P Class=KRCC>
볼츠만은 다윈의 학설에서<br>
정적이지 않은 생명의 진화,
<SYNC Start=2483034><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2483151><P Class=KRCC>
때로는 점프처럼 진행되는<br>
진보라는 아이디어를 좋아했고
<SYNC Start=2489793><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2490078><P Class=KRCC>
이전의 관념적 사고방식에<br>
바탕을 둔 과학으로는
<SYNC Start=2496511><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2496698><P Class=KRCC>
생명 현상을 해석할 수 없다는<br>
시각에 찬동했습니다
<SYNC Start=2502682><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2505241><P Class=KRCC>
볼츠만의 생각은 칸토어나 다윈<br>
못지 않은 혁명적인 것이었습니다
<SYNC Start=2509242><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2509489><P Class=KRCC>
그 자신은 별로<br>
의식하지 않았지만 말입니다
<SYNC Start=2512641><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2513094><P Class=KRCC>
하지만 그가 살던 시기에는
<SYNC Start=2515875><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2515995><P Class=KRCC>
새로운 생각이 사회의 구조를 무너뜨릴지<br>
모른다는 두려움이 팽배해 있었습니다
<SYNC Start=2522561><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2523586><P Class=KRCC>
19세기말 비엔나 사회는<br>
정치, 철학, 예술, 과학 등
<SYNC Start=2528731><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2528917><P Class=KRCC>
어느 분야에서든 확실성과 원리를<br>
추구하던 분위기였습니다
<SYNC Start=2534514><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2534951><P Class=KRCC>
그러나, 모든 것을 통합하고<br>
떠받칠 수 있는 철학적 토대는
<SYNC Start=2539635><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2539663><P Class=KRCC>
결코 발견되지 않을듯 했습니다
<SYNC Start=2542702><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2542874><P Class=KRCC>
비엔나 대학은 철학을<br>
찬양하는 뜻에서
<SYNC Start=2545818><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2545866><P Class=KRCC>
구스타프 클림트에게<br>
천장 벽화를 부탁했는데
<SYNC Start=2549393><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2549498><P Class=KRCC>
이것이 그 결과물입니다
<SYNC Start=2551450><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2561486><P Class=KRCC>
이것을 모욕이라고 느낀 스무명의 교수들이<br>
벽화를 내리라고 청원하기도 했답니다
<SYNC Start=2567310><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2572888><P Class=KRCC>
어찌됐든 확실성을 찬양하려는<br>
노력은 실패한 셈입니다
<SYNC Start=2577027><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2581114><P Class=KRCC>
이 시대의 급진주의자들은 확실성을 좇는<br>
구식 질서가 허물어질것을 알았습니다
<SYNC Start=2587988><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2590311><P Class=KRCC>
하지만 비엔나 사회는 새로움을<br>
받아들일 준비가 되어 있지 않았고
<SYNC Start=2594216><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2594239><P Class=KRCC>
볼츠만은 갈 곳이 없었습니다
<SYNC Start=2596905><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2598157><P Class=KRCC>
논쟁에 대처하는 방식에서도<br>
그의 완고한 성격이 드러나는데
<SYNC Start=2607354><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2608413><P Class=KRCC>
비판을 단순한 비판이 아니라<br>
자신에 대한 공격으로 받아들였습니다
<SYNC Start=2614568><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2615111><P Class=KRCC>
그는 열정에 찬 인물이었고
<SYNC Start=2618095><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2618991><P Class=KRCC>
아주 명랑했다가도<br>
극도로 우울해지는 등
<SYNC Start=2624777><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2624973><P Class=KRCC>
감정의 기복이 심했습니다
<SYNC Start=2629182><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2631233><P Class=KRCC>
나이가 들고 논쟁에 지쳐가면서
<SYNC Start=2634952><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2635077><P Class=KRCC>
조울증은 더 심해졌습니다
<SYNC Start=2637850><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2637962><P Class=KRCC>
자신의 이론을 납득시키느라<br>
더 많은 에너지를 빼앗겼습니다
<SYNC Start=2644333><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2644813><P Class=KRCC>
그는 "이 목표는 내 삶의 의미이며<br>
모든것을 희생할 가치가 있다."고 했습니다
<SYNC Start=2651811><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2653977><P Class=KRCC>
볼츠만은 생애 마지막 10년동안<br>
연구는 전혀 하지 않았습니다
<SYNC Start=2661206><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2661509><P Class=KRCC>
그보다는 철학적 논쟁에 몰두하며<br>
자신의 주장을 분명히 밝히고
<SYNC Start=2669612><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2669802><P Class=KRCC>
같은 개념을 되풀이하여 주장하는<br>
저술 활동에 집중했습니다
<SYNC Start=2676597><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2676770><P Class=KRCC>
앞으로 나아가지 못하는<br>
쳇바퀴를 돌리고 있었던거죠
<SYNC Start=2682348><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;

<SYNC Start=14287><P Class=ENCC>
Beneath the surface of the world are the rules of science.
<SYNC Start=18522><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=18799><P Class=ENCC>
But beneath them, there is a far deeper set of rules.
<SYNC Start=22820><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=22997><P Class=ENCC>
A matrix of pure mathematics which explains the nature of the rules of science
<SYNC Start=29244><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=29342><P Class=ENCC>
and how it is we can understand them in the first place.
<SYNC Start=33101><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=35970><P Class=ENCC>
<font color=lightgreen>To see a world in a grain of sand<br>
And a heaven in a wild flower,</font>
<SYNC Start=41832><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=41983><P Class=ENCC>
<font color=lightgreen>Hold infinity in the palm of your hand<br>
And eternity in an hour</font>
<SYNC Start=48829><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=49131><P Class=ENCC>
What is the system that everything has to adhere to, if there is no God?
<SYNC Start=55364><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=56333><P Class=ENCC>
You had these ideas and.. you had to be very careful because any moment they would bite you.
<SYNC Start=61851><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=61897><P Class=ENCC>
They sounded great but they were very dangerous.
<SYNC Start=64665><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=67012><P Class=ENCC>
But then of course people get scared, so they pull back from the edge of the precipice.
<SYNC Start=72536><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=72806><P Class=ENCC>
Well, this is not a matter of liking it or not. It is..
<SYNC Start=76953><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=77133><P Class=ENCC>
you have here this proof and.. one has to live with it.
<SYNC Start=81560><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=81974><P Class=ENCC>
This film is about how a small group of the most brilliant minds
<SYNC Start=86131><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=86247><P Class=ENCC>
unravelled our old cozy certainties about math and the universe.
<SYNC Start=91035><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=91331><P Class=ENCC>
It is also about how once they had looked at these problems they could not look away,
<SYNC Start=96463><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=96512><P Class=ENCC>
and pursued the questions to the brink of insanity and then over it to madness and suicide.
<SYNC Start=103673><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=104084><P Class=ENCC>
But for all their tragedies, what they saw is still true.
<SYNC Start=108928><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=109231><P Class=ENCC>
Their contemporaries largely rejected the significance of their work,
<SYNC Start=112544><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=112642><P Class=ENCC>
and we have yet to fully inherit it.
<SYNC Start=115384><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=115573><P Class=ENCC>
Today, we still stand only on the threshold of the world they saw.
<SYNC Start=121738><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=148288><P Class=ENCC>
My name is David Malone.
<SYNC Start=150380><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=150588><P Class=ENCC>
And this is my homage to four great thinkers, who without most of us even having heard of them,
<SYNC Start=156709><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=156804><P Class=ENCC>
have profoundly influenced the nature of our age.
<SYNC Start=160833><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=160934><P Class=ENCC>
and whose stories have, I think, an important message for us today.
<SYNC Start=165844><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=172232><P Class=ENCC>
This is Halle, a provincial town in eastern Germany
<SYNC Start=175816><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=175983><P Class=ENCC>
where Martin Luther once preached the Reformation.
<SYNC Start=179574><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=180547><P Class=ENCC>
Our story starts here at the town's university with the mathematics professor,
<SYNC Start=184644><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=184663><P Class=ENCC>
a man called Georg Cantor who started a revolution he never really meant to start
<SYNC Start=189489><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=189680><P Class=ENCC>
but which eventually threatened to shake the whole of mathematics and science on its foundations.
<SYNC Start=194996><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=195360><P Class=ENCC>
And he started his revolution by asking himself a simple question.
<SYNC Start=198558><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=198803><P Class=ENCC>
"How big is infinity?"
<SYNC Start=201939><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=211928><P Class=ENCC>
Cantor is wonderful because it's so crazy.
<SYNC Start=214129><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=214366><P Class=ENCC>
It's the equivalent of being on drugs.<br>
It's just an incredible feat of imagination.
<SYNC Start=221055><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=221381><P Class=ENCC>
Georg Cantor is one of the greatest mathematicians of the world.
<SYNC Start=227008><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=232499><P Class=ENCC>
Others before him, going back to the ancient Greeks at least, had asked the question.
<SYNC Start=237846><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=238182><P Class=ENCC>
But it was Cantor who made the journey no one else ever had and found the answer.
<SYNC Start=244517><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=246072><P Class=ENCC>
But he paid a price for his discovery.
<SYNC Start=248650><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=251967><P Class=ENCC>
This is the only bust there is of Georg Cantor.
<SYNC Start=255068><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=255303><P Class=ENCC>
It was made just one year before he died.
<SYNC Start=258302><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=258655><P Class=ENCC>
And he died utterly alone in an insane asylum.
<SYNC Start=262412><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=263026><P Class=ENCC>
The question is: what could the greatest mathematician of his century
<SYNC Start=266803><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=266837><P Class=ENCC>
have seen that could drive him insane?
<SYNC Start=270092><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=279561><P Class=ENCC>
If all that Cantor had seen was mathematics, then his story would be of limited interest.
<SYNC Start=285362><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=285530><P Class=ENCC>
But from the beginning, Cantor realized his work had far wider significance.
<SYNC Start=291744><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=300365><P Class=ENCC>
He believed it could take the human mind towards greater, transcendent truth and certainty.
<SYNC Start=306743><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=306939><P Class=ENCC>
What he never suspected was that eventually his math
<SYNC Start=310326><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=310372><P Class=ENCC>
would make that certainty ever more elusive,
<SYNC Start=313603><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=313743><P Class=ENCC>
perhaps even destroy the possibility of ever reaching it.
<SYNC Start=318636><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=326246><P Class=ENCC>
If you want to understand Georg Cantor
<SYNC Start=327969><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=328071><P Class=ENCC>
you have to understand he was a religious man, though not in a conventional sense.
<SYNC Start=332278><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=332447><P Class=ENCC>
He almost certainly came to this church
<SYNC Start=334998><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=335154><P Class=ENCC>
but that's not his God.
<SYNC Start=337102><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=337264><P Class=ENCC>
He wasn't interested in the God whose mysteries were redemption and resurrection.
<SYNC Start=342066><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=347718><P Class=ENCC>
Ever since he was just a boy he had heard what he called
<SYNC Start=351001><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=351158><P Class=ENCC>
'a secret voice calling him to mathematics'.
<SYNC Start=355464><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=355686><P Class=ENCC>
That voice which he heard all his life, in his mind, was God.
<SYNC Start=360736><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=361029><P Class=ENCC>
So for Cantor, his mathematics of infinity had to be correct.
<SYNC Start=365704><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=365848><P Class=ENCC>
Because God, the true infinite, had revealed it to him.
<SYNC Start=370370><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=370583><P Class=ENCC>
<font color=lightgreen>These things which are now hidden from you will be brought into the light..</font>
<SYNC Start=375490><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=376045><P Class=ENCC>
If you look at Cantor's last major publication about set theory in 1895, it starts with three aphorisms.
<SYNC Start=382707><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=382848><P Class=ENCC>
and his third motto is from the bible and it's from Corinthians.
<SYNC Start=386658><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=386996><P Class=ENCC>
And it's "that which has been hidden to you will eventually be brought into the light."
<SYNC Start=392895><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=393079><P Class=ENCC>
And Cantor, I think, really believed he was the messenger,
<SYNC Start=396046><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=396068><P Class=ENCC>
that this theory that had been hidden, he was God's means
<SYNC Start=400438><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=400489><P Class=ENCC>
of bringing this theory of the infinite to the world.
<SYNC Start=402994><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=403486><P Class=ENCC>
There is no contradiction for Cantor between his religious thinking and his mathematics.
<SYNC Start=410390><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=411423><P Class=ENCC>
He understood or he was thinking that his ideas were a gift of God.
<SYNC Start=418179><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=418570><P Class=ENCC>
My view was that Cantor was trying to understand God,
<SYNC Start=421676><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=421962><P Class=ENCC>
and that this was really like a 'mathematical theology' that he was doing.
<SYNC Start=426402><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=427050><P Class=ENCC>
Cantor's God was the creator God, the God who set the planets spinning in their orbits
<SYNC Start=432093><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=432434><P Class=ENCC>
whose mysteries were the eternal and perfect laws of motion.
<SYNC Start=436820><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=438844><P Class=ENCC>
Laws whose discovery had launched the modern world
<SYNC Start=442247><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=442445><P Class=ENCC>
and allowed us to see the world as curves, trajectories and forces
<SYNC Start=447293><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=447410><P Class=ENCC>
and which would one day even put men on the moon.
<SYNC Start=451083><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=451848><P Class=ENCC>
The eternal certainties laid down by God which Newton and Leibniz had discovered.
<SYNC Start=457943><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=458246><P Class=ENCC>
And it was infinity which lay at the heart of it all.
<SYNC Start=461573><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=461817><P Class=ENCC>
But there was a problem with it.
<SYNC Start=463968><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=465006><P Class=ENCC>
If you look at that beautiful smooth curve of motion, you notice it's not actually smooth.
<SYNC Start=470489><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=470586><P Class=ENCC>
It's made of an infinite number of infinitesimally small straight lines.
<SYNC Start=474933><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=475159><P Class=ENCC>
And each line is an instant in which nothing moves.
<SYNC Start=478154><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=478350><P Class=ENCC>
But like frames of film, if you run one after another you get motion. And it works.
<SYNC Start=483642><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=483837><P Class=ENCC>
The whole thing relies on infinity, but it works.
<SYNC Start=486925><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=487113><P Class=ENCC>
Because it worked, everyone said, "All right, we don't understand infinity. Just leave it alone."
<SYNC Start=492083><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=492560><P Class=ENCC>
Cantor comes along and says, "No, if this whole thing rests on infinity we have to understand it."
<SYNC Start=497616><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=497872><P Class=ENCC>
Now remember Cantor was a religious man.
<SYNC Start=499966><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=500086><P Class=ENCC>
So for him, that symbol isn't just a scientific mystery. It's a religious mystery as well.
<SYNC Start=505455><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=505720><P Class=ENCC>
Here's the math that God uses to keep creation in motion.
<SYNC Start=509221><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=509462><P Class=ENCC>
And at its heart lies the deeper mystery of infinity.
<SYNC Start=513186><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=514218><P Class=ENCC>
But it was a mystery that had so far defied every mind that had looked at it.
<SYNC Start=519169><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=520233><P Class=ENCC>
The first modern thinker to confront the infinite was Galileo.
<SYNC Start=524597><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=524920><P Class=ENCC>
And he tried to do it using the circle.
<SYNC Start=527563><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=527795><P Class=ENCC>
This is how he did it.
<SYNC Start=528808><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=528979><P Class=ENCC>
First of all, draw a circle.
<SYNC Start=531621><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=532304><P Class=ENCC>
Now put a triangle inside it, then a square. Keep on going, keep adding sides.
<SYNC Start=536531><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=536777><P Class=ENCC>
Eventually you realize what the circle is.
<SYNC Start=539163><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=539334><P Class=ENCC>
It's a shape with infinitely many, infinitesimally small sides,
<SYNC Start=543723><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=544062><P Class=ENCC>
which seems great. Now you hold the infinite and the infinitesimal in your hands.
<SYNC Start=548697><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=549009><P Class=ENCC>
But as soon as he'd done that, he realized he'd actually opened up a horrible illogical paradox.
<SYNC Start=553843><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=554511><P Class=ENCC>
Because he said, let's draw a bigger circle outside.
<SYNC Start=558344><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=558505><P Class=ENCC>
And now with an infinitely sharp pencil, draw from the center,
<SYNC Start=562630><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=562669><P Class=ENCC>
infinitely sharp lines, one for each of the lines of the inner circle.
<SYNC Start=567812><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=567970><P Class=ENCC>
All right, there's infinite number of them. They should be enough for the inner circle.
<SYNC Start=570775><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=570854><P Class=ENCC>
Now extend those lines out to meet the outer circle.
<SYNC Start=574755><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=575192><P Class=ENCC>
Those lines are diverging,
<SYNC Start=577262><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=577305><P Class=ENCC>
which means when you get to the outer circle, if you look really carefully there would be gaps.
<SYNC Start=581828><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=581843><P Class=ENCC>
They won't be enough!
<SYNC Start=584322><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=584537><P Class=ENCC>
And Galileo just said, "That makes no sense. If there is an infinite number it should be enough!"
<SYNC Start=589912><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=590214><P Class=ENCC>
at which point he said we just can't understand the infinite.
<SYNC Start=592923><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=592959><P Class=ENCC>
Maybe God can, but with our finite minds we can't.
<SYNC Start=597562><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=597757><P Class=ENCC>
So, let's use the concept if we must.
<SYNC Start=600775><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=601120><P Class=ENCC>
But let's not try and understand infinity.
<SYNC Start=603347><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=603566><P Class=ENCC>
And that's exactly how they left it until Georg Cantor came along.
<SYNC Start=607520><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=611446><P Class=ENCC>
At first it must have seemed to Cantor that God really was on his side.
<SYNC Start=615983><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=616212><P Class=ENCC>
In the space of only a few years he married, began a family
<SYNC Start=619806><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=619993><P Class=ENCC>
and published his first groundbreaking paper about Infinity.
<SYNC Start=624675><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=625922><P Class=ENCC>
Where previously infinity had just been a vague number without end
<SYNC Start=629830><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=629861><P Class=ENCC>
Cantor saw a whole new world opening up.
<SYNC Start=633120><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=635264><P Class=ENCC>
Cantor did a new step and he said, "I want to add one plus one."
<SYNC Start=641406><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=641781><P Class=ENCC>
And Cantor said, "Okay, why not I can add infinity plus infinity? .."
<SYNC Start=648911><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=649390><P Class=ENCC>
".. That's also possible." And this was the starting point of his theory.
<SYNC Start=654730><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=656401><P Class=ENCC>
Cantor found he could add and subtract infinities, and in fact
<SYNC Start=660475><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=660548><P Class=ENCC>
discovered there was a vast new mathematics of the infinite.
<SYNC Start=665650><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=666371><P Class=ENCC>
You really finally feel for the first time that the infinite is no longer
<SYNC Start=670501><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=670599><P Class=ENCC>
this amorphous concept - "Well it's infinite, and that's all you can say about it."
<SYNC Start=675100><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=675344><P Class=ENCC>
But Cantor says no, there's a way you can make this very precise and I can make it very definite as well.
<SYNC Start=680597><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=685952><P Class=ENCC>
By 1872, Cantor is a man inspired.
<SYNC Start=689158><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=689552><P Class=ENCC>
He's already grasped and understood the nature of real infinity which no one before him had done.
<SYNC Start=695338><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=695922><P Class=ENCC>
But in that same year he comes up here to the Alps
<SYNC Start=698501><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=698553><P Class=ENCC>
to meet the only other man who really understood his work,
<SYNC Start=701864><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=701998><P Class=ENCC>
a mathematician called Richard Dedekind.
<SYNC Start=704081><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=704952><P Class=ENCC>
And this time is probably the happiest and most inspired period of Cantor's life.
<SYNC Start=711493><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=712226><P Class=ENCC>
Within a year of their meeting he announces an astonishing discovery
<SYNC Start=716629><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=716926><P Class=ENCC>
that beyond infinity there's another larger infinity
<SYNC Start=721781><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=721947><P Class=ENCC>
and possibly even a whole hierarchy of different infinities.
<SYNC Start=726934><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=730644><P Class=ENCC>
Though it is contrary to every intuition,
<SYNC Start=733154><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=733630><P Class=ENCC>
Cantor began to see that some infinities are bigger than others.
<SYNC Start=737980><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=738146><P Class=ENCC>
He already knew that when you looked at the number line
<SYNC Start=740764><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=740902><P Class=ENCC>
it divided up into an infinite number of whole numbers and fractions.
<SYNC Start=745625><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=745885><P Class=ENCC>
But Cantor found that as he looked closer at this line,<br>
that infinite though the fractions are,
<SYNC Start=751237><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=751535><P Class=ENCC>
each one is separated from the next by a wilderness of other numbers.
<SYNC Start=756841><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=756925><P Class=ENCC>
Irrational numbers like π,
<SYNC Start=759125><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=759165><P Class=ENCC>
which require an infinite number of decimal places just to define them.
<SYNC Start=763377><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=763710><P Class=ENCC>
Against all logic, the infinity of these numbers was unmeasurably, uncountably larger than the first.
<SYNC Start=771612><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=771928><P Class=ENCC>
What had frightened Galileo, Cantor had proved.
<SYNC Start=775126><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=775362><P Class=ENCC>
There was a larger infinity.
<SYNC Start=778113><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=781704><P Class=ENCC>
Today, Cantor's genius continues to inspire the work of some of the greatest mathematicians.
<SYNC Start=787402><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=787747><P Class=ENCC>
Greg Chaitin is recognized as one of the most brilliant.
<SYNC Start=792003><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=792640><P Class=ENCC>
Well infinity was always there but they tried to contain it, they tried to keep it in a cage.
<SYNC Start=799815><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=800098><P Class=ENCC>
And people would talk about potential infinity not as opposed to actual infinity.
<SYNC Start=804474><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=804610><P Class=ENCC>
But Cantor just goes all the way. He just goes totally berserk.
<SYNC Start=808023><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=808263><P Class=ENCC>
And then you find that you have infinities and bigger infinities and even bigger infinities
<SYNC Start=812208><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=812383><P Class=ENCC>
and for any infinite series of infinities, there are infinities that go bigger than all of them.
<SYNC Start=818749><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=818973><P Class=ENCC>
And you get numbers so big that you wonder how you could even name them.
<SYNC Start=823385><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=823414><P Class=ENCC>
Infinities are so big that you can't even give them names.
<SYNC Start=826421><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=826598><P Class=ENCC>
This is just fantastic stuff.
<SYNC Start=829745><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=829959><P Class=ENCC>
So in a way what he's saying is: "Given any set of concepts, I'm going to invent something that's bigger!"
<SYNC Start=834819><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=835130><P Class=ENCC>
So this is paradoxical essentially.
<SYNC Start=837879><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=838391><P Class=ENCC>
So there's something inherently ungraspable that escapes you from this conception.
<SYNC Start=844948><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=845248><P Class=ENCC>
So it's absolutely breathtaking, it's great stuff.
<SYNC Start=848021><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=848203><P Class=ENCC>
Now it may not have anything to do with partial differential equations,
<SYNC Start=850418><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=850471><P Class=ENCC>
building bridges, designing air foils. But who cares?
<SYNC Start=854514><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=855353><P Class=ENCC>
The sheer audacity of Cantor's ideas had thrown open the doors and changed mathematics forever.
<SYNC Start=862173><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=862362><P Class=ENCC>
And he knew it.
<SYNC Start=864246><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=864733><P Class=ENCC>
We can't know exactly how he felt.
<SYNC Start=867003><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=867191><P Class=ENCC>
But Greg Chaitin has also felt those rare moments of profound insight.
<SYNC Start=872731><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=878581><P Class=ENCC>
Here we are down in the forest, and..
<SYNC Start=881508><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=881759><P Class=ENCC>
we can't see very far in any direction.
<SYNC Start=884627><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=884850><P Class=ENCC>
And you struggle up knowing the fact that you are tired and weary.
<SYNC Start=889013><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=889163><P Class=ENCC>
You struggle up a mountain, and the higher you go the more beautiful and breathtaking the views are.
<SYNC Start=895419><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=897353><P Class=ENCC>
And then, if you're lucky you get to the top of the mountain.
<SYNC Start=902510><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=903693><P Class=ENCC>
That can be a transcendental experience.
<SYNC Start=906854><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=907209><P Class=ENCC>
A spiritual person would say they feel closer to God.
<SYNC Start=911156><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=914191><P Class=ENCC>
You have this breathtaking view. All of a sudden you can see in all directions and things make sense.
<SYNC Start=921302><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=921796><P Class=ENCC>
It's beautiful to understand something that you couldn't understand before.
<SYNC Start=925628><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=925724><P Class=ENCC>
The problem is, the moment you understand one thing that raises more questions.
<SYNC Start=930220><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=930341><P Class=ENCC>
So in other words the moment you climb one mountain then you see off in the distance,
<SYNC Start=934629><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=934817><P Class=ENCC>
behind the haze, much higher mountains.
<SYNC Start=936749><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=938197><P Class=ENCC>
His theory is all about the fact that the mountains get higher and higher,
<SYNC Start=941912><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=942292><P Class=ENCC>
and no range is equal enough because there are always mountain ranges
<SYNC Start=945313><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=945380><P Class=ENCC>
beyond any range that you can understand or conceive of.
<SYNC Start=948654><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=949164><P Class=ENCC>
So this is tremendously liberating effect on mathematics, or ought to.
<SYNC Start=952664><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=952888><P Class=ENCC>
But then of course people get scared. So they pull back from the edge of the precipice.
<SYNC Start=958291><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=960030><P Class=ENCC>
What was inspiring for Cantor frightened his critics.
<SYNC Start=964053><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=964173><P Class=ENCC>
They saw mathematics as the pursuit of clarity and certainty.
<SYNC Start=967853><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=967989><P Class=ENCC>
Everything Cantor was doing, his irrational numbers and his illogical infinities
<SYNC Start=972753><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=972842><P Class=ENCC>
seemed to them to be eating away at certainty.
<SYNC Start=975411><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=976080><P Class=ENCC>
He soon faced a deep and implacable hostility.
<SYNC Start=979515><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=980882><P Class=ENCC>
This is the main lecture theater in the university where Cantor spent his entire professional life.
<SYNC Start=985679><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=986059><P Class=ENCC>
A life that he felt trapped in, and I think with some justification.
<SYNC Start=989847><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=990156><P Class=ENCC>
Other mathematicians actually tried to prevent Cantor publishing his papers.
<SYNC Start=994483><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=994826><P Class=ENCC>
Cantor always dreamed that he'd receive an invitation
<SYNC Start=997436><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=997504><P Class=ENCC>
to one of the great universities like Vienna or Berlin.
<SYNC Start=1000622><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1000736><P Class=ENCC>
But they were invitations which never came.
<SYNC Start=1002809><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1003157><P Class=ENCC>
And he was also attacked personally.
<SYNC Start=1005133><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1005245><P Class=ENCC>
The great mathematician Henri Poincare said
<SYNC Start=1008320><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1008898><P Class=ENCC>
that Cantor's mathematics was a sickness from which one day math would recover.
<SYNC Start=1013813><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1014022><P Class=ENCC>
And worse, his one time friend and teacher Kroneker
<SYNC Start=1018412><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1018464><P Class=ENCC>
said that Cantor was a corruptor of youth.
<SYNC Start=1021523><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1021796><P Class=ENCC>
Cantor felt that he and his ideas were being caged or quarantined here
<SYNC Start=1027518><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1027614><P Class=ENCC>
as if they were some kind of sickness.
<SYNC Start=1030254><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1030512><P Class=ENCC>
The genie got out of the bottle. It was a very dangerous genie.
<SYNC Start=1034002><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1034073><P Class=ENCC>
because the concepts that Cantor played with are intrinsically, inherently self-contradictory.
<SYNC Start=1040257><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1040720><P Class=ENCC>
And people don't like to face up to that. They've emasculated set theory. They have this..
<SYNC Start=1045168><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1045395><P Class=ENCC>
this version which is safe, called Zermelo-Fraenkel set theory, which is sort of a watered-down.
<SYNC Start=1051870><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1052090><P Class=ENCC>
But you see that takes all the fun out of it.
<SYNC Start=1054306><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1054352><P Class=ENCC>
For me, the fun of Cantor was that he was playing on the edge.
<SYNC Start=1059196><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1059467><P Class=ENCC>
You know the idea was you had these ideas and..
<SYNC Start=1062178><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1062291><P Class=ENCC>
you had to be very careful because at any moment they would bite you.
<SYNC Start=1065487><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1065570><P Class=ENCC>
They sounded great but they were very dangerous.
<SYNC Start=1068011><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1068082><P Class=ENCC>
You see they were almost self-contradictory.
<SYNC Start=1070607><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1070800><P Class=ENCC>
The notion of 'the set of everything' for example is self-contradictory.
<SYNC Start=1075103><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1076470><P Class=ENCC>
And people got frightened.
<SYNC Start=1077894><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1079390><P Class=ENCC>
His critics feared Cantor was going to dislodge the certainty and clarity vital to mathematics and logic
<SYNC Start=1085732><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1085875><P Class=ENCC>
which might not be able to be put back.
<SYNC Start=1088726><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1089081><P Class=ENCC>
It seemed Cantor had opened math to the very thing that was supposed to save us from irresolvable uncertainty.
<SYNC Start=1095636><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1096333><P Class=ENCC>
Cantor knew the only way to convince his critics was to make his theory complete.
<SYNC Start=1101294><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1101635><P Class=ENCC>
Could he show there was a logic to his infinities - some system that bound them altogether.
<SYNC Start=1107824><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1109271><P Class=ENCC>
What he absolutely must decide now is what's the relationship between them.
<SYNC Start=1114213><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1114486><P Class=ENCC>
If he can do that, then his theory is perfect.
<SYNC Start=1117665><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1117927><P Class=ENCC>
If he can't, then all he has is bits.
<SYNC Start=1121016><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1121466><P Class=ENCC>
So he has to decide what's the relationship between them.
<SYNC Start=1124706><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1124966><P Class=ENCC>
And that question is the 'continuum hypothesis'.
<SYNC Start=1128299><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1129425><P Class=ENCC>
No matter how isolated he became, the more he was opposed, the more he struggled.
<SYNC Start=1135119><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1135444><P Class=ENCC>
Where another person might have given up, Cantor didn't.
<SYNC Start=1138986><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1143440><P Class=ENCC>
Clinical psychologist Dr. Louis Sass suggests
<SYNC Start=1146911><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1147031><P Class=ENCC>
it is precisely this ability to be isolated which is key to Cantor's genius.
<SYNC Start=1152785><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1153634><P Class=ENCC>
I think that willingness to step into a realm
<SYNC Start=1157684><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1157830><P Class=ENCC>
beyond taken-for-granted is absolutely essential.
<SYNC Start=1161636><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1161719><P Class=ENCC>
But I think if you are a person who takes that step
<SYNC Start=1164003><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1164069><P Class=ENCC>
in a way you're already doomed to living outside in some way.
<SYNC Start=1167615><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1168052><P Class=ENCC>
So it's not as if it's only the intellectual project itself that takes you out there.
<SYNC Start=1173661><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1173859><P Class=ENCC>
There's something about you as a person, that is, just..
<SYNC Start=1176662><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1176698><P Class=ENCC>
that unnaturalness so to speak comes so naturally to you.
<SYNC Start=1181369><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1184191><P Class=ENCC>
Cantor was trapped.
<SYNC Start=1185734><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1185909><P Class=ENCC>
There were too many things that went to the core of who he was for him to be able to give up.
<SYNC Start=1191391><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1192315><P Class=ENCC>
When Cantor was just a boy, his father sent him a letter
<SYNC Start=1195811><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1195968><P Class=ENCC>
which became his most precious possession and which he carried with him all his life.
<SYNC Start=1201343><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1203525><P Class=ENCC>
In it his father told him how the whole family looked to him to achieve greatness.
<SYNC Start=1208927><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1209080><P Class=ENCC>
How he would come to nothing if he did not have the courage to overcome criticism and adversity,
<SYNC Start=1214652><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1214800><P Class=ENCC>
how he must trust in God to guide him and never give up.
<SYNC Start=1219239><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1222257><P Class=ENCC>
And he never did.
<SYNC Start=1224226><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1225284><P Class=ENCC>
I think here you come to the root of the problem for Cantor of a theory
<SYNC Start=1230764><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1230820><P Class=ENCC>
that he was certain was correct,
<SYNC Start=1234076><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1234230><P Class=ENCC>
in part because he believed that it had come to him as a message from God.
<SYNC Start=1238579><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1238715><P Class=ENCC>
There's a very important religious aspect to Cantor's struggle to deal with the infinite
<SYNC Start=1244647><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1244840><P Class=ENCC>
and face the problems of not being able to resolve
<SYNC Start=1248502><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1248558><P Class=ENCC>
many of the open questions that he himself raised for the first time.
<SYNC Start=1251610><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1256799><P Class=ENCC>
By 1884, Cantor has been working solidly on the continuum hypothesis for over 2 years.
<SYNC Start=1262318><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1262780><P Class=ENCC>
At the same time the personal and professional attacks on him have become more and more extreme.
<SYNC Start=1268487><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1268755><P Class=ENCC>
In fact he writes to a friend saying he's not sure he can take them any more.
<SYNC Start=1272076><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1272183><P Class=ENCC>
And indeed he can't.
<SYNC Start=1273755><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1273899><P Class=ENCC>
By May of that year, he has a massive nervous breakdown.
<SYNC Start=1277086><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1277305><P Class=ENCC>
His daughter describes how his whole personality is transformed.
<SYNC Start=1280938><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1281200><P Class=ENCC>
He would rant and rave and then fall completely and uncommunicatively silent.
<SYNC Start=1286700><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1286984><P Class=ENCC>
Eventually he is brought here to the Nervenklinik in Halle which is an asylum.
<SYNC Start=1292717><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1294229><P Class=ENCC>
Today we'd call it, Cantor suffered from manic depressive illness.
<SYNC Start=1299154><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1299350><P Class=ENCC>
From Cantor's time we're left the case notes of
<SYNC Start=1303263><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1303388><P Class=ENCC>
most of his psychiatrists describe in the notes for example
<SYNC Start=1309730><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1309901><P Class=ENCC>
we see that he at times was quite disturbed, screaming,
<SYNC Start=1316029><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1316379><P Class=ENCC>
and see that he was really suffering from severe bouts of mania.
<SYNC Start=1322403><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1322587><P Class=ENCC>
Sometimes he would be angry
<SYNC Start=1325467><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1326881><P Class=ENCC>
and he would have ideas of grandeur, and sometimes he also had ideas of persecution.
<SYNC Start=1332617><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1359286><P Class=ENCC>
After his breakdown everything about Cantor is transformed.
<SYNC Start=1362789><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1363858><P Class=ENCC>
He tells a friend he's not sure he'll ever be able to do mathematics again.
<SYNC Start=1367128><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1367328><P Class=ENCC>
He asks the university if he can stop teaching math and teach philosophy instead.
<SYNC Start=1371648><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1371969><P Class=ENCC>
But interestingly during this whole time,
<SYNC Start=1374121><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1374174><P Class=ENCC>
despite having claimed he'll not be able to do mathematics again,
<SYNC Start=1377086><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1378203><P Class=ENCC>
he never stops working on the continuum hypothesis.
<SYNC Start=1381466><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1381526><P Class=ENCC>
It's as if he just can't put it down. Can't look away.
<SYNC Start=1385600><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1387287><P Class=ENCC>
You can only think, 'I must find a proof.'
<SYNC Start=1390907><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1391638><P Class=ENCC>
This I can understand, because when you are a mathematician
<SYNC Start=1394814><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1394889><P Class=ENCC>
then you are for all the time a mathematician.
<SYNC Start=1397900><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1398183><P Class=ENCC>
It's a form of living for you.
<SYNC Start=1401977><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1402323><P Class=ENCC>
You must think about mathematics and you can't think anything else the whole day.
<SYNC Start=1409981><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1410182><P Class=ENCC>
You are thinking and thinking and thinking
<SYNC Start=1412595><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1412806><P Class=ENCC>
and you say 'I must find it.'
<SYNC Start=1416054><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1416496><P Class=ENCC>
I must, I must, I must.. you can't think of anything else.
<SYNC Start=1420854><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1421480><P Class=ENCC>
In August of 1884 he writes a letter to his friend and colleague,
<SYNC Start=1426607><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1426701><P Class=ENCC>
the last man who still publishes his work, a man called Mittag-Leffler.
<SYNC Start=1430943><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1431270><P Class=ENCC>
And the letter is ecstatic.
<SYNC Start=1432860><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1433057><P Class=ENCC>
He says, "I've done it. I've proved the continuum hypothesis, it's true."
<SYNC Start=1437909><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1438243><P Class=ENCC>
And he promises that he'll send the proof in the following weeks.
<SYNC Start=1441544><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1442228><P Class=ENCC>
But the proof never comes.
<SYNC Start=1443884><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1444170><P Class=ENCC>
Instead, three months later the second letter arrives.
<SYNC Start=1447800><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1447907><P Class=ENCC>
And in this one, you can feel Cantor's embarrassment.
<SYNC Start=1451727><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1451824><P Class=ENCC>
He says, "I'm sorry, I should never have claimed that I'd proved it."
<SYNC Start=1455518><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1456092><P Class=ENCC>
He says, "My beautiful proof lies all in ruins."
<SYNC Start=1460392><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1461326><P Class=ENCC>
And you can see the wreckage of his work in the letter.
<SYNC Start=1466163><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1468505><P Class=ENCC>
But then three weeks after that
<SYNC Start=1470517><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1471364><P Class=ENCC>
this letter arrives and in it he says,
<SYNC Start=1474632><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1475030><P Class=ENCC>
"I've proved that the continuum hypothesis is not true."
<SYNC Start=1479139><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1480404><P Class=ENCC>
And this pattern continues.
<SYNC Start=1482216><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1482592><P Class=ENCC>
He proves that it is true,
<SYNC Start=1485182><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1485394><P Class=ENCC>
and then he's convinced that it's not true. Back and forth.
<SYNC Start=1488555><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1489086><P Class=ENCC>
And in fact what Cantor is doing is driving himself slowly insane.
<SYNC Start=1494348><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1494782><P Class=ENCC>
One of things that will happen, especially in the early stages,
<SYNC Start=1497666><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1497694><P Class=ENCC>
and the stages just before a schizophrenic break, but also in the early stages,
<SYNC Start=1501913><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1502021><P Class=ENCC>
would be that the patient is in a way looking too hard at the world in too concentrated a way.
<SYNC Start=1508093><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1508210><P Class=ENCC>
There's a kind of rigidity of the perceptual stance.
<SYNC Start=1512267><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1516372><P Class=ENCC>
When he could not solve the continuum hypothesis, Cantor came to describe the infinite as an abyss,
<SYNC Start=1522986><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1523384><P Class=ENCC>
a chasm perhaps.. between what he had seen and what he knew must be there,
<SYNC Start=1529089><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1529205><P Class=ENCC>
but could never reach.
<SYNC Start=1530554><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1533997><P Class=ENCC>
What can happen is that some object in the world that the rest of us would
<SYNC Start=1539911><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1540021><P Class=ENCC>
just consider as a sort of random thing there seems somehow symbolic in some way.
<SYNC Start=1545210><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1545554><P Class=ENCC>
<font color=lightgreen>I must, I must, I must..</font>
<SYNC Start=1549543><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1558233><P Class=ENCC>
There is a way in which in order to understand something you have to look very hard at it.
<SYNC Start=1561856><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1561969><P Class=ENCC>
But you also have to be able to sort of move away from it and kind of see it in a kind of context.
<SYNC Start=1566740><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1567005><P Class=ENCC>
And the person who stares too hard can often lose that sense of context.
<SYNC Start=1571213><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1577709><P Class=ENCC>
Cantor never fully recovered.
<SYNC Start=1579670><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1579794><P Class=ENCC>
For the rest of his life, he would be drawn back to work on the problem he could not solve
<SYNC Start=1584842><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1585195><P Class=ENCC>
and each time it would hurt him profoundly.
<SYNC Start=1589084><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1609761><P Class=ENCC>
1899, Cantor returned once again to work on the continuum hypothesis.
<SYNC Start=1614626><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1614908><P Class=ENCC>
And again it made him ill, and he returned to the asylum.
<SYNC Start=1618664><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1619306><P Class=ENCC>
He was just recovering from this breakdown
<SYNC Start=1622370><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1622998><P Class=ENCC>
when his son Rudolph died suddenly, four days short of his 13th birthday.
<SYNC Start=1629194><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1639471><P Class=ENCC>
Cantor wrote to a friend saying
<SYNC Start=1641401><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1641450><P Class=ENCC>
how his son had had a great musical talent, just as he had had when he was a boy.
<SYNC Start=1645957><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1646362><P Class=ENCC>
But he had set music aside in order to go into mathematics.
<SYNC Start=1650709><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1651297><P Class=ENCC>
And now with the death of his son,
<SYNC Start=1653465><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1653539><P Class=ENCC>
he felt that his own dream of musical fulfillment had died with him.
<SYNC Start=1658211><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1679787><P Class=ENCC>
<font color=lightgreen>Papa!</font>
<SYNC Start=1681071><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1688041><P Class=ENCC>
Cantor went on to say that he could no longer even remember why he himself
<SYNC Start=1693622><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1693690><P Class=ENCC>
had left music in order to go into math.
<SYNC Start=1696685><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1696854><P Class=ENCC>
That secret voice which had once called him on to mathematics
<SYNC Start=1701635><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1701699><P Class=ENCC>
and given meaning to his life and work..
<SYNC Start=1704350><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1704727><P Class=ENCC>
The voice he identified with God..
<SYNC Start=1707121><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1707476><P Class=ENCC>
That voice too had left him.
<SYNC Start=1710646><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1713477><P Class=ENCC>
Here we have to leave Georg Cantor.
<SYNC Start=1715872><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1716060><P Class=ENCC>
Because, if we treat Cantor's story in isolation
<SYNC Start=1719128><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1719162><P Class=ENCC>
it makes it into a tragic but obscure footnote to the broader sweep of history.
<SYNC Start=1724356><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1724693><P Class=ENCC>
Whereas in fact, the fear that Cantor had dislodged something
<SYNC Start=1728998><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1729064><P Class=ENCC>
was part of a much broader feeling that things once felt to be solid were slipping.
<SYNC Start=1735415><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1735604><P Class=ENCC>
A feeling seen more clearly in the story of his great contemporary,
<SYNC Start=1739101><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1739267><P Class=ENCC>
a man called Ludwig Boltzmann.
<SYNC Start=1741559><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1743197><P Class=ENCC>
Just as Cantor had revolutionary ideas in mathematics and was opposed
<SYNC Start=1746861><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1747046><P Class=ENCC>
so Boltzmann, his contemporary, had revolutionary ideas in physics and was equally opposed.
<SYNC Start=1752871><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1753846><P Class=ENCC>
This is Ludwig Boltzmann's grave.
<SYNC Start=1755902><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1756390><P Class=ENCC>
That, carved on it, is the equation which killed him.
<SYNC Start=1760284><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1769303><P Class=ENCC>
And it did so because like Cantor, Boltzmann's ideas were out of step with his times.
<SYNC Start=1775369><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1779357><P Class=ENCC>
Cantor had undermined the ideal of a timeless and perfect logic in math.
<SYNC Start=1783708><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1784306><P Class=ENCC>
Boltzmann's formula and his destiny was to undermine the ideal of a timeless order in physics.
<SYNC Start=1790655><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1791076><P Class=ENCC>
Together, their ideas were part of a general undermining of certainty
<SYNC Start=1795702><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1795841><P Class=ENCC>
in the wider world outside of math and physics.
<SYNC Start=1798950><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1808130><P Class=ENCC>
Boltzmann's and Cantor's times craved certainty
<SYNC Start=1811239><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1811481><P Class=ENCC>
in politics, in art as well as in science and philosophy.
<SYNC Start=1815351><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1819262><P Class=ENCC>
They were times that looked on the surface solid and certain
<SYNC Start=1823066><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1823100><P Class=ENCC>
but felt themselves to be teetering and sliding.
<SYNC Start=1826098><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1826691><P Class=ENCC>
The old order was dying and it was as if they could already feel disaster's gravitational pull.
<SYNC Start=1834097><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1834865><P Class=ENCC>
In Vienna which was called by Karl Kraus 'laboratory for apocalypse'.
<SYNC Start=1841144><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1841318><P Class=ENCC>
There was this feeling that this political construct of The Habsburg Empire
<SYNC Start=1848455><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1848550><P Class=ENCC>
couldn't last for much longer.
<SYNC Start=1850158><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1853283><P Class=ENCC>
They were very strange times.
<SYNC Start=1855860><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1856183><P Class=ENCC>
On the one hand, those in power spent 20 years building the monuments of Imperial Vienna,
<SYNC Start=1862537><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1862553><P Class=ENCC>
to declare, that this order, firm on its foundations, would last forever.
<SYNC Start=1868140><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1870710><P Class=ENCC>
The rich man would always be in his castle,
<SYNC Start=1873739><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1873944><P Class=ENCC>
the poor man always at his gate.
<SYNC Start=1876886><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1877804><P Class=ENCC>
But on the other hand, the empire was actually on its last legs.
<SYNC Start=1882538><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1882820><P Class=ENCC>
And the intellectual tenor of the times was summed up by the poet Hoffmanstahl,
<SYNC Start=1887822><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1887959><P Class=ENCC>
who said that what previous generations believed to be firm was in fact, what he called
<SYNC Start=1894934><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1895061><P Class=ENCC>
'das Gleitende'
<SYNC Start=1897678><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1898118><P Class=ENCC>
- the slipping or sliding away of the world.
<SYNC Start=1901440><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1903741><P Class=ENCC>
I think that describes the feeling in Vienna.. in other places too,
<SYNC Start=1909868><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1909936><P Class=ENCC>
but particularly in Vienna, in this capital of an empire that hadn't crumbled yet.
<SYNC Start=1914838><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1914951><P Class=ENCC>
But it looked like that too.. break-down.. this characterizes it very well.
<SYNC Start=1921504><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1925145><P Class=ENCC>
And it was against this background that the scientific questions of Boltzmann's times were understood.
<SYNC Start=1931363><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1934701><P Class=ENCC>
This is the great courtyard of the University of Vienna.
<SYNC Start=1937329><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1937619><P Class=ENCC>
And these are the busts of all of the greats who've ever taught here.
<SYNC Start=1940933><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1941156><P Class=ENCC>
Boltzmann's here too.
<SYNC Start=1942679><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1943050><P Class=ENCC>
But many of his contemporaries men, more influential in their day even than he was,
<SYNC Start=1947368><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1947538><P Class=ENCC>
lined up to oppose him and his ideas.
<SYNC Start=1950209><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1951312><P Class=ENCC>
But their opposition was as much ideological as it was scientific.
<SYNC Start=1955888><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1957188><P Class=ENCC>
The physics of Boltzmann's time was still the physics of certainty, of an ordered universe
<SYNC Start=1962814><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1963016><P Class=ENCC>
determined from above by predictable and timeless God given laws.
<SYNC Start=1968088><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1969184><P Class=ENCC>
Boltzmann suggested that the order of the world was not imposed from above by God
<SYNC Start=1974891><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1974956><P Class=ENCC>
but emerged from below from the random bumping of atoms.
<SYNC Start=1979501><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1979628><P Class=ENCC>
A radical idea, at odd with his times, but the foundation of ours.
<SYNC Start=1985337><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1988363><P Class=ENCC>
Professor Mussardo lives and works in Trieste on the Adriatic coast
<SYNC Start=1992778><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1992877><P Class=ENCC>
not far from where Boltzmann's life ended.
<SYNC Start=1995834><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1995943><P Class=ENCC>
He is an expert on Boltzmann and works on the same kind of physics.
<SYNC Start=2000301><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2000945><P Class=ENCC>
I think that there were two reasons why he could not get fully accepted
<SYNC Start=2006848><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2006896><P Class=ENCC>
and recognized by the German physicists.
<SYNC Start=2012589><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2012901><P Class=ENCC>
One of them was that he was based all his theory on atom that people cannot see.
<SYNC Start=2021239><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2022560><P Class=ENCC>
And this was the reason of the very very strong criticism by Ernst Mach,
<SYNC Start=2027338><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2027565><P Class=ENCC>
one of the most influential philosopher of science at that time.
<SYNC Start=2033602><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2033983><P Class=ENCC>
So the critic of Mach was simply:
<SYNC Start=2036758><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2036880><P Class=ENCC>
"Atom? I cannot see, I don't need it, they do not exist. So why we should bring them in the game?"
<SYNC Start=2044047><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2045421><P Class=ENCC>
Worse than insisting on the reality of something people could not see,
<SYNC Start=2049273><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2049471><P Class=ENCC>
to base physics on atoms meant to base it on things whose behaviour was too complex to predict,
<SYNC Start=2055573><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2055793><P Class=ENCC>
which meant an entirely new kind of physics - one based on probabilities, not certainties.
<SYNC Start=2062197><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2064202><P Class=ENCC>
Then there was a second aspect. It was revolutionary as well.
<SYNC Start=2068284><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2068808><P Class=ENCC>
And this consists in putting and emphasizing the role of probability in the physics world.
<SYNC Start=2077059><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2078726><P Class=ENCC>
And people were used to law of physics or science as exact,
<SYNC Start=2086206><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2087791><P Class=ENCC>
once established they stay there forever, there is no room for uncertains.
<SYNC Start=2093773><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2094175><P Class=ENCC>
So there introducing into the game two ingredients like atom invisible,
<SYNC Start=2100218><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2100302><P Class=ENCC>
and probability, namely the fact that it's not certain,
<SYNC Start=2104048><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2104172><P Class=ENCC>
you can predict probably what's going on but not certainly..
<SYNC Start=2109128><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2109331><P Class=ENCC>
well this really contrasted very very much with the scientific spirit of the time.
<SYNC Start=2115963><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2116280><P Class=ENCC>
And therefore this produced a trouble.
<SYNC Start=2120505><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2122201><P Class=ENCC>
Boltzmann's genius was that he could accept probability.
<SYNC Start=2126385><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2126671><P Class=ENCC>
This meant he could begin to understand complex phenomena like fire and water and life,
<SYNC Start=2132672><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2132804><P Class=ENCC>
things which traditional physics - the physics of mechanics - never could.
<SYNC Start=2137768><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2138289><P Class=ENCC>
But because his solution relied on probability, and probability undermines certainty,
<SYNC Start=2144348><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2144408><P Class=ENCC>
no one wanted to hear him.
<SYNC Start=2146802><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2151002><P Class=ENCC>
And so just like Cantor, he faced implacable opposition
<SYNC Start=2154936><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2154970><P Class=ENCC>
which he too found extremely difficult to deal with.
<SYNC Start=2158807><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2159710><P Class=ENCC>
It seems like Boltzmann was just the wrong man in the wrong place..
<SYNC Start=2162602><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2162752><P Class=ENCC>
Absolute. Absolute. It's true..
<SYNC Start=2167132><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2170203><P Class=ENCC>
If he'd just had his idea 20 years later..
<SYNC Start=2172782><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2172881><P Class=ENCC>
Later and in England, he'd have been the most successful physicist of that time. It's true.
<SYNC Start=2180008><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2180220><P Class=ENCC>
Somehow he met all his enemies. So he met Ernst Mach often.. they even crossed in a very..
<SYNC Start=2191621><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2191802><P Class=ENCC>
- All his enemies but none of his friends.<br>
- Not his friends, it's true.
<SYNC Start=2194585><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2198304><P Class=ENCC>
It is not hard to see how Boltzmann's ideas were so radically at odds with his times.
<SYNC Start=2203608><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2203907><P Class=ENCC>
Especially when applied not just to physics but to the social world.
<SYNC Start=2208547><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2209835><P Class=ENCC>
Classical science, classical physics, gives you this image of a God ordered creation,
<SYNC Start=2215436><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2215541><P Class=ENCC>
where everything is set in stone according to perfect and eternal rules,
<SYNC Start=2220114><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2220366><P Class=ENCC>
everything is predictable, everything has its place, and everything is in its place.
<SYNC Start=2225833><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2227063><P Class=ENCC>
But when you come here to the Central Cemetery of Vienna,
<SYNC Start=2230304><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2230514><P Class=ENCC>
you see the idealized vision of that idea.
<SYNC Start=2233583><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2233714><P Class=ENCC>
Because here everything is predictable.
<SYNC Start=2236270><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2236442><P Class=ENCC>
Everybody does have a place and everybody is in their place.
<SYNC Start=2239614><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2240076><P Class=ENCC>
But the problem is, while such certainty might seem desirable politically,
<SYNC Start=2245671><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2245714><P Class=ENCC>
the real world, the living world, the world described by thermodynamics just isn't like that.
<SYNC Start=2252219><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2254879><P Class=ENCC>
A timeless and perfect world never changes, but it is dead.
<SYNC Start=2259522><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2259619><P Class=ENCC>
The real world, the thermodynamic world is alive precisely because it is full of change.
<SYNC Start=2265934><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2268005><P Class=ENCC>
But of course that life-giving change also brings with it disorder and decay.
<SYNC Start=2274676><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2275342><P Class=ENCC>
But then the problem arises. If you then say, well
<SYNC Start=2277996><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2278162><P Class=ENCC>
Newtonian mechanics on which you're depending is reversible in time.
<SYNC Start=2282187><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2282249><P Class=ENCC>
So how can you derive a law which is asymmetrical in time
<SYNC Start=2285938><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2286154><P Class=ENCC>
from basic principles which are symmetrical in time.
<SYNC Start=2289367><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2290096><P Class=ENCC>
You run a clock backwards, it's just as good Newtonian physics as if you run it forwards.
<SYNC Start=2293842><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2294124><P Class=ENCC>
Yet the entropy increases in the future.
<SYNC Start=2296894><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2300644><P Class=ENCC>
But it is precisely this accumulation of disorder and decay
<SYNC Start=2304783><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2304869><P Class=ENCC>
that science calls entropy which Boltzmann had understood.
<SYNC Start=2309339><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2314086><P Class=ENCC>
In short this is really the arrow of time.
<SYNC Start=2316666><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2316807><P Class=ENCC>
You can measure the arrow of time just seeing how things become more and more disordered.
<SYNC Start=2323410><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2323747><P Class=ENCC>
So it's a natural tendency in the world that Boltzmann quantified precisely.
<SYNC Start=2329784><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2331104><P Class=ENCC>
Indeed I call him the 'genius of disorder'.
<SYNC Start=2334686><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2338227><P Class=ENCC>
Boltzmann's work on entropy showed why
<SYNC Start=2340944><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2340956><P Class=ENCC>
no system can be perfect, why there must always be some disorder.
<SYNC Start=2345933><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2346059><P Class=ENCC>
It also revolutionized the idea of time in physics.
<SYNC Start=2349737><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2355521><P Class=ENCC>
In classical physics, everything including time can run equally well forwards as backwards.
<SYNC Start=2362328><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2362886><P Class=ENCC>
Yet in thermodynamics, while everything else is reversible,
<SYNC Start=2366807><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2366879><P Class=ENCC>
time moves inexorably forward like an arrow.
<SYNC Start=2371172><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2374494><P Class=ENCC>
The idea of entropy had a profound philosophical and political significance.
<SYNC Start=2379848><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2380325><P Class=ENCC>
Entropy is what changes the ticking of a clock into the destroyer of all things.
<SYNC Start=2385871><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2386130><P Class=ENCC>
It is what underlies the inexorable passage from youth to old age.
<SYNC Start=2391178><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2393595><P Class=ENCC>
Entropy is decay, and with decay nothing lasts forever.
<SYNC Start=2398519><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2405452><P Class=ENCC>
Boltzmann had in essence captured mortality in an equation.
<SYNC Start=2410875><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2415268><P Class=ENCC>
Physics now declared that no order, not even a God given one would last forever.
<SYNC Start=2422401><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2426658><P Class=ENCC>
That there was no natural order that God had set in stone
<SYNC Start=2430780><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2430786><P Class=ENCC>
had already been pointed out by the scientist Boltzmann most admired
<SYNC Start=2435080><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2435749><P Class=ENCC>
Charles Darwin.
<SYNC Start=2437565><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2441942><P Class=ENCC>
In place of timeless perfection was a dance of evolution and extinction.
<SYNC Start=2447199><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2447926><P Class=ENCC>
With his equation of entropy,
<SYNC Start=2450322><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2450386><P Class=ENCC>
Boltzmann brought this picture of constant change into the very heart of physics itself.
<SYNC Start=2456444><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2462137><P Class=ENCC>
Did Boltzmann understand the similarity?
<SYNC Start=2464658><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2464911><P Class=ENCC>
Almost certainly.
<SYNC Start=2466262><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2466912><P Class=ENCC>
When Boltzmann was asked how his century would be remembered
<SYNC Start=2470472><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2470692><P Class=ENCC>
he did not choose a physicist. He said it would be the century of Darwin.
<SYNC Start=2476147><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2477764><P Class=ENCC>
So he likes in Darwin the momentum, the evolution of life that is not static,
<SYNC Start=2483034><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2483151><P Class=ENCC>
and the fact that there is progress, progress as sometimes this jump in it,
<SYNC Start=2489793><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2490078><P Class=ENCC>
and the fact that he cannot address life aspect
<SYNC Start=2496511><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2496698><P Class=ENCC>
with ideas of science that before was kind of ideological ground.
<SYNC Start=2502682><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2505241><P Class=ENCC>
Boltzmann's ideas, like Cantor's and Darwin's, were revolutionary
<SYNC Start=2509242><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2509489><P Class=ENCC>
even though he did not think of them that way.
<SYNC Start=2512641><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2513094><P Class=ENCC>
But his times were frightened times..
<SYNC Start=2515875><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2515995><P Class=ENCC>
times when people felt new ideas could upset society's fragile structure and bring it down.
<SYNC Start=2522561><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2523586><P Class=ENCC>
At the end of the 19th century, Viennese society was searching for some certainty, some principle,
<SYNC Start=2530118><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2530314><P Class=ENCC>
whether it was in politics, philosophy, the arts or science.
<SYNC Start=2534514><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2534951><P Class=ENCC>
But there didn't appear to be any philosophy capable of holding everyone together
<SYNC Start=2539635><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2539663><P Class=ENCC>
upon which everything else could be based.
<SYNC Start=2542702><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2542874><P Class=ENCC>
So when the university commissioned Gustav Klimt
<SYNC Start=2545818><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2545866><P Class=ENCC>
to paint the ceiling to celebrate philosophy
<SYNC Start=2549393><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2549498><P Class=ENCC>
this is what they got.
<SYNC Start=2551450><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2561486><P Class=ENCC>
Such was the outrage that twenty professors petitioned to have the painting removed.
<SYNC Start=2567310><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2572888><P Class=ENCC>
Now whatever else it is, it's not a celebration of certainty.
<SYNC Start=2577027><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2581114><P Class=ENCC>
The radicals of Boltzmann's times knew the old order with its worn out certainties was doomed.
<SYNC Start=2587988><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2590311><P Class=ENCC>
But Viennese culture was not ready to embrace the new.
<SYNC Start=2594216><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2594239><P Class=ENCC>
And Boltzmann was caught in the middle.
<SYNC Start=2596905><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2598157><P Class=ENCC>
As a scientist his personality entered deeply into the game because he was very stubborn.
<SYNC Start=2607354><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2608413><P Class=ENCC>
Not self ironic.. he could not take it criticism, he always take personally.
<SYNC Start=2614568><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2615111><P Class=ENCC>
And Boltzmann was definitely a passion man.
<SYNC Start=2618095><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2618991><P Class=ENCC>
He used to swing rapidly from incredible joy to deep depression.
<SYNC Start=2629182><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
